column13: 3563. Brown, F. Feb. 12. Cut-outs for arc lamps. Lamps h a v i n g airtight casings and globes, for use in air containing combustible gas or dust, are provided with cutouts arranged to disconnect the lamps if the globes are broken so that enclosed liquid or compressed gas escapes. In one arrangement, air is compressed into the casing and globe through a non-return valve, and raises a piston against a contactspring by which the lamp circuit is completed. In a modification shown, two concentric globes a, m a r e used, and air is compressed through a valve into a space between them which communicates with a cylinder c containing a piston operating a switch lever c<4>. In another arrangement, a liquid is circulated through pipes and between two concentric globes, the inner of which floats in the liquid and carries metal pieces to close the circuit through pieces fixed on the lamp casing ; the inner globe is kept in position by guides.

column12: Methods and systems for preventing the misconfiguration of optical networks using a network management system
column13: The present invention provides methods and systems for preventing the misconfiguration of OSRP and OS/ISIS networks using a NMS, including: configuring a GNE with an address and NE ID for the NMS; forwarding topology information through a management interface to a NMS server; at the NMS server, copying a topology database of all NEs that are connected to the GNE; and, at the NMS server, launching NE mediators for all of the NEs in the topology database. Each NE mediator includes a listener that listens for updates and topology changes within the network.

column13: A device and method is shown and described for the purpose of providing situational awareness to third party observers through a portable emergency light system. The system includes a casing, a power supply, a control panel, and a series of lights. The lights are configured to illuminate according to one or more elected illumination patterns. The particular patterns may represent given situations or conditions, and provide notice to observers related to a warning, caution, or defined perimeter. The sequential blinking, brightness, and coloring of the emitted light may vary. Multiple units may be connected to provide an elongated series of lights. This is ideally useful for roadside assistance and emergency personnel.

column13: 6259. Brown, F. W. March 12. Spring wheels with flexible rim with link connexion to drums having spring resistance to rotary motion.-Consists of further constructional details in the wheels described in Specifications 2262/10 and 30,038/10, characterized by a flexible tread supported on bell-crank levers connected either directly to springs or to spring-controlled inner rims. The tread band is built up of concentric spring steel bands 11, 15, 17, 18, Fig. 9, spaced by alternating blocks. The two series of brackets 2 to which the bell-crank levers 1 are pivoted rest on bands bridged by strips carrying a single central series of blocks 14 with the object of supporting the tread centrally. The rubber or leather tread 21. Fig. 13, is carried by a metal band 18, which may be detachably secured to a metal band 17 by stud-like keys 30, Fig. 14. The keys are passed through registering slots 29 and, after turning through a right-angle, are locked by a plate 31, which itself is locked by another plate 32. The edges of the tread are secured to the side covers 35, which are secured to the wheel frame at 40. The sides of the wheel are closed by inner and outer covers 42, 49, with inspection-doors. A flexible joint 44 permanently secured to the edges of the tyre cover has an adjustable wire edge 47 seated in the edge of the inner cover. The outer cover bears against packing 48. Helical springs 54 are placed between the outer arms of the bell-crank levers and the innermost tread band. A spring-controlled jointed-lever connexion is arranged between the levers 1 and the wheels 5 in order to reduce the recoil. The main springs 6, Fig. 1, controlling the wheels 5 are enclosed within casings and are connected by a link 8 to an adjustable point on a lever 7 pivoted at one end to the main wheel body and at the other end to a link 9, the object being to increase the strain on the spring with the displacement so as to obtain a uniform elastic resistance. The recoil of the inner wheels is clamped by the spring system 77. An adjustable initial tension of the helical spring 6, Figs. 6 and 7, is obtained by fitting between the coils thereof a thin helical spring 80, to which are secured packing - pieces 81. The main spring is duplicated at 83. The lubricating-system consists of an oil reservoir 92, Figs. 1 and 12, with a pump 110 and supply pipes 95, 97, 99 leading to the various moving elements. The supply of oil to the bell-crank lever pivots is controlled by centrifugally-acting valves 111, Figs. 9 and 11. A weight 120 on a rod 121 acts so as to open more or less through the sliding tube 116 the aperture 117 in the chamber 111. The pump rod 102 engages a squared spindle on the dipper 104, so that the dipper can be turned to reach the oil in any position of the reservoir.

column12: A vehicle wheel hub bearing unit with a removable sensor
column13:
A vehicle wheel hub bearing unit comprises:
 a stationary, radially outer race (14) having a portion (20) projecting radially outwardly; a rotatable, radially inner race (15a); an encoder (17) fixed for rotation with the rotatable radially inner race (15a) in close proximity to the inboard side of a flange (11) fast for rotation with the hub (10) and projecting radially outwardly therefrom; a sensor mount element (22) fixed to the radially outwardly projecting portion (20); a sensor body (25) mounted in removable manner to the mount element (22) and incorporating a sensor element (32) facing in operation the encoder (17).

The truck comprises a front part pivotally connected to a rear part via a king pin 14. A steering motor drives gear 12 meshed with gear 18 to cause the steering effect. The front wheels 20 are driven by a motor 30 via differential 32 and clutches 26, 28 are located in the respective half shafts 22, 24. When the steering angle exceeds a predetermined amount, eg 45 degrees, in either direction, the corresponding clutch is actuated to disconnect drive to the wheel which is nearer to the centre about which the truck is turning. Thereafter the outside one of the wheels 20 is driven and the other three are free to turn in either direction or remain stationary as the vehicle is manoeuvred by the driver. The drive may be hydrostatic with a motor in the rear part driving a pump feeding a motor at each driven wheel. At the threshold steering angle, a spool valve cuts the supply to the inner wheel motor. Alternatively, the drive may be electric with an electric motor for each driven wheel, the inner motor being switched out of circuit at the threshold angle. <IMAGE>

column13: Human hair is treated with peroxymonosulphuric or -phosphoric acid, an organic peroxy acid or a salt or ester of said acids and subsequently dyed with a solution of a reactive dye. The organic peroxy acids specified are peracetic, diperbrassylic and perbenzoic acid and they may be used as their urea adducts. The preferred compound is the triple salt 2KHSO5. KHSO4. K2SO4. Alkali salts may be present with the peroxy compound to give the preferred pH range 3-10 as well as thickeners, soaps or detergents, and perfumes. Examples are given.

column13: A narrow aisle forklift truck is enabled to turn at extreme steering angles and minimise or avoid tyre scrub or the like by having a differential mechanism D allowing the driven wheels 14 to turn at different speeds, and arranging for the maximum steering angle to result in intersection of the axes A1, A2 of the front and rear wheels at a point lying within the track of the driven wheels. A vehicle 1 comprising: a frame 2; a steered wheel 6 centrally mounted at or towards a front end of the frame 2; and two stabiliser wheels 9, 10 mounted at or towards the front end of the frame 2 to respective sides of the central steered wheel 6 and fixed vertically to the frame 2, the vehicle 1 further comprising a suspension mechanism 19 between the frame 2 and the central steered wheel 6 to permit vertical travel of the central steered wheel 6 relative to the frame 2. In use, if the stabiliser wheels come to take some of the weight of the vehicle, the steered wheel is able to move downwards relative to the frame and maintain contact with the ground. The invention is particularly applicable to mobility scooters.

A lift truck (10, Figure 1) comprises (i) a lifting device (14, Figure 1), with a mast 24 and forks 26, pivotally attached to the truck body (12, Figure 1) about a first axis 32, and (ii) at least one steerable wheel 34 proximal the lifting device which is pivotable about a second axis 40 to enable steering of the truck. Means are provided for independently pivoting the lifting device (14, Figure 1) about the first axis 32 and the steerable wheel 34 about the second axis 40. Preferably the first axis 32 is positioned closer to the main body of the truck than the second axis 40, and the steerable wheel 34 may be located below the mast 24 of the lifting device to provide enhanced stability of the truck when in use. The steerable wheel 34 may be pivotally attached to the lifting device at plate 42, or may otherwise be pivotally attached to the body of the truck and therefore be independent of the lifting device. Preferably the direction of movement of the truck is determined by the steerable wheel 34 and/or the lifting device (14, Figure 1), and the goods can be directed in a different direction to the movement of the truck. This enables easier use of the truck in narrow aisles (Figure 3).

column13: 23,755. Brown, F. W. Nov. 18. Motor road vehicles.- Two wheels placed side by side and mounted in a framework attached to the vehicle are connected to each other and if necessary to a driving- wheel by a coupling which allows radial motion but no relative rotation, so that blocks on one tyre are kept in alinement with recesses in the other tyre, the object being to avoid an obstacle affecting the wheel as a whole. The wheels w<2>, w<1>, Fig. B, are supported on short axles a3, a<4>, carried by vertical members a<6>, Fig. A, of a frame f attached to the vehicle at a<1> through springs s, Fig. B. The live axle a<2> carries a disk wheel w<4> and is connected by a coupling, shown separately in Fig. 3, to a disk on the axle a<3> which is supported in the bearing member a<6>. The bars a<6> are connected to the framework f by parallel motions and by springs so that finally the wheels are resiliently supported, have independent vertical motion always parallel to the frame f, but always rotate together. As a further means, the wheels are connected inside their rims by four parallel motion devices m, Fig. 1, shown separately in Fig. 5, set horizontally in one wheel and connected to another four, set vertically on the other wheel, by means of universal joints m' connected also to four extensions on the coupling shown in Fig. 3, placed between the wheels. This consists of a floating cross c to which is pivoted on one side at e', e, two pairs of parallel motions n, n<1>, n, connected to one wheel at n<2>, n<3>, Fig. 1, and on the other side a similar set placed to act perpendicularly and connected to the other wheel. The springs, which separate the frame f from the axle supports a<6>, are supported by extensions a<10> on the latter, Fig. A, and are arranged so that all do not come into action at once, but with increased effect after a little compression has occurred. In Fig. C, the central spring is shorter than the others which hold rods s<7> formed with collars s<8> so that one half only of each spring becomes effective finally. In Figs. 11<A> and 11<B>, the springs are in pairs, so that one member comes into action after the other. They are connected to the frame at their outer ends and to the bars a<6> by the central fixtures. These springs may be replaced by pneumatic cushions. In Fig. A, additional parallel motions m<6>, m<7> are placed on extensions a<7> of the bar a<6>, or these motions may be dispensed with and the members a<7> extended to embrace the ends of the frame for the same purpose. In Fig. 7, the axle of the wheel w<1>, which has wire spokes, is formed with an annular web fitted into a recess in the hub b<2> provided with balls. The axle a<3> of the wheel w<2> is separated by balls from a bearing b in the member a<6> which is connected by parallel motions and springs to the frame f again separated by ball bearings from a cylindrical member u<1> connected to the axle a<3> by the coupling described, and fitted with a sprocket-wheel u<2>. In Fig. 12, each axle is tapered and fitted with bushes k<1>, k<2>, having tapered boxes, which may be adjusted to tighten the wheels on the axles. Driving is accomplished by providing the wheel w' with a cog-wheel r gearing with a pinion r' driven through a coupling fitted against a disk on its axle r<3>.

column13: 19,592. Brown, F. W. Sept. 28. Motor road vehicles.-Comprises means for driving a spring wheel for vehicles and velocipedes consisting of two wheels placed side by side on separate axles enclosed in and separated by springs from a light steel framework secured to the axle, in such manner as to allow play of the springs. Each wheel has independent radial motion and a tyre formed of alternate gaps and projections, the object being to prevent any obstacle from affecting the wheel as a whole. The framework, Figs. A and B, has a lower horizontal part f<1> and an upper part f<2> passing over the top. On a driving-wheel there are additional stays f<7>, f<8>, Fig. B, fixed to the end of the main axle a<1> through which a live axle passes. The driving-wheel w may be chain - driven or attached to the live axle, and to keep the vertical motion independent a modified Oldham coupling or equivalent means is placed between the driving- wheel and a disk w<1> on the axle a<3> carrying the wheel w<3>, and also between the two wheels. The axles a, a<3> are supported in vertical bars x, x<1>, which are connected to the framework at each end by a parallel-motion device, shown in Fig. G, consisting of a plate v and pivoted links v'. Helical springs s, or carriage springs, are placed between the upper part of the framework and plates r secured behind the bars x, x<1>, which are also connected to the end of the framework by pivoted guiding-links c', c', Fig. A. The adopted form of coupling for transmitting driving motion between the wheels is shown in Fig. F. Pivoted links e<4>, e<5> connect the wheel at one side to a floating plate l<3> which is connected to the wheel at the other side (not shown) by the pivoted levers e<6>, e'. The tread projection on one tyre coincides with the gap in the other tyre, and may overlap to extend the whole width. Each projection may be of rubber secured by a plate and radial bolt, or may be of iron with rounded ends and rubber fillings let into recesses in the parts which first meet the ground and held by radial bolts. Figs. 10 and 11 show an additional way of connecting the two wheels by levers g<1>, g<2> which allow radial motion, limited according to the preceding. Fig. 9 shows a driving-wheel of a motor-bicycle. The hub m is recessed to revolve outside a tube n which has a vertical arm n<1> bearing on a spring and is fixed to the end of a controlling-arm pivoted at the bottom bracket. The driving-wheel w<9> is fixed on the inner end of a tube n<3> which revolves within a bearing n<2> fixed to the frame. The outer end of the tube n<3> drives the axle a through the medium of a coupling such as described. Fig. 14 shows an alternative form of parallel motion, and Fig. 5 an alternative coupling described in the Provisional Specification. Links l are pivoted at one end to one wheel and at the other slotted end to a crossbar P. Links l<3> are pivoted to the cross-bar and to the other wheel at their slotted ends. There is also an application e, e<1> of the Oldham coupling, the object being to get independent vertical motion along with the rotation.

A flexible ultrasonic contact transducer comprises an unpoled polymeric film layer and a poled piezo film layer. Electrode shielding layers are disposed on outer surfaces of the unpoled polymeric film layer and poled piezo film layer. A quarter wave reflector is disposed between inner surfaces of the two layers. An ultrasonic contact transducer array comprises a common poled piezo film layer and a common backing/insulating layer. A plurality of quarter wave reflector elements are disposed between inner surfaces of the poled piezo film layer and backing/insulating layer. Shielding electrodes are disposed on the outer surfaces of the two layers. A polymeric shielding layer is preferably disposed around the quarter wave reflectors. Lead means provide an electrical path from the quarter wave reflectors to a common edge of the array.

A narrow aisle forklift truck (Figure 1) has a pivot between the mast and body and means for turning the mast relative to the body so as to steer the truck. The mast has a load extensor/retractor (28) between the forks (26) and the mast (24). This enables insertion and extraction in particularly narrow aisles relative to the dimensions of the truck and its load.

A narrow aisle lift truck has hydraulic control of steering with means to prevent oversteer by reaction between the wheels and the ground. When steering left, hydraulic fluid flows via line A to the motor and exhausts from the motor through the opposite line B and via a relief valve F which is opened by the pressure in line A. When the steering angle remains constant there is no pressure in A and valve F is closed so that any forces tending to deflect the steering either way are resisted by the one-way flow valves in line A and the closed relief valve F. Bypass C, D are arranged to open under excess pressure so that in the event of for example accidental impact raising the pressure in one or other line the appropriate relief valve opens and this guards against damage to the circuit.

column13: 119,677. Brown, F. W. Sept. 29, 1917. Submarines, trapping, &c. - Comprises nets having torpedoes which are drawn into position by means of specially arranged cables and pulley blocks. Fig. 1 shows in elevation a net supported by floats 62, and Figs. 2 and 4 show in plan and crcss-section respectively the position of the net after being .struck by a submarine 16, the net being drawn away from the base cable 1. When this occurs, the hauling ropes 17, 34 pull the blocks 14 further apart and cause the cable 20 to draw the torpedo 21 horizontally along the net until it is under the submarine, and it is then exploded. The exploding mechanism in the torpedo is operated by a Bowden wire and hinged levers; pulley arms and checking a.rms also are described together with the method of releasing the torpedo cab. e from the pulley arms. Torpedoes are arranged on both sides of the net, and means are provided to ensure the torpedo on the off side of the net being inoperative when the near side of the net is struck by the submarine. The horizontal wires of the net may be hinged in the middle and have hooks 36 and spring arms 37, Fig. 9, for holding the stay rope &c. 38 of the submarine. A modification is described in which the bottom of the net is drawn up when required by electrically-driven screws. The top of the net may be drawn down to allow vessels to pass over it.

A flexible ultrasonic contact transducer comprises an unpoled polymeric film layer and a poled piezo film layer. Electrode shielding layers are disposed on outer surfaces of the unpoled polymeric film layer and poled piezo film layer. A quarter wave reflector is disposed between inner surfaces of the two layers. An ultrasonic contact transducer array comprises a common poled piezo film layer and a common backing/insulating layer. A plurality of quarter wave reflector elements are disposed between inner surfaces of the poled piezo film layer and backing/insulating layer. Shielding electrodes are disposed on the outer surfaces of the two layers. A polymeric shielding layer is preferably disposed around the quarter wave reflectors. Lead means provide an electrical path from the quarter wave reflectors to a common edge of the array.

column13: 13,330. Brown, F. W. May 29. Tyres, elastic other than pneumatic.-Relates to helical spring tyres of the kind described in Specification No. 25,754, A.D. 1896, circumferential and transverse sections of one form being shown in Figs. 17 and 18 respectively. The tyre consists of a double row of flattened helical springs s, corresponding pairs of which are connected together and supported by flat steel wire ties t, as shown in Fig. 18. Round the outer ends of the springs is a flexible extensible tread-band h, preferably formed from a number of thin steel bands placed one outside the other and secured together by clip3, an outer circle h<1> of leather being attached by wires j<6>. Each spring is detachably secured to this treadband by clips j<4> having eyelets to receive bent wires e<8>, or by some similar device. The base-band k is extensible, and the springs are attached to it in a corresponding manner. The rubber and canvas cover, encloses the whole tyre, and its stiffened or thickened edges u are placed between the band k and the rim l. The ends of the band k are fastened to wires y<1>, y<2> which are connected to a plate p<1>, rotation of which by means of the pin p and handle p<2> tightens or slackens the band k and thus attaches or detaches the tyre. In modifications, the springs may be arranged either alternately on each side of the rim, or singly instead of in pairs, or a single spring may be placed intermediate to consecutive pairs ; the baseband may be replaced by two circumferential side rods ; a suitably-pivoted lever may be employed instead of the tightening - device p<1> ; the springs may be elliptical or flattened ; and some of the coils may be indented to allow for the ties t.

column13: 2262. Brown. F. W. Jan. 29. [Cognate Application 17,577/10.] Metallic spring bodies and cores; block tyres. -A flexible laminated steel rim is supported by bell-crank levers, the inner ends of which engage tangentially the rims of drums rotating on the hub against the resistance of helical springs. In the form shown, three drums a<1>, a<2>, a3, Figs. B and C, are mounted on ball bearings. Each is fitted with a compound spring s', s<2>. At one end a lever b is pivoted centrally on a block b<1> adjustable through a bar e<9> fixed to the wheel body r<6>, Fig. A. The ends of the springs are connected by links to the ends of the lever. The spring s<2> is pivoted at its other end to a bar, fixed to the body and carrying a lever l<1>. The other end of this lever bears against a stop e<10>, which keeps the springs in tension, and pivoted to it is a bar connected to the spring s<1> and pivoted centrally on a lever e<2>. One end of the lever rests on a stop e<11> fixed to the body; the other end is connected by a pivoted link l to a spoke f of the wheel. The lever l is adjustable at both ends, and the arrangement is such that the leverage increases as the springs extend, with the result that the rate of increase of resistance is reduced and a long spring range is obtained. In order to damp the recoil of the wheel, an air brake is fitted. A cylinder n<4> is carried by the body. A lever n<6> divided into a long and short arm is pivoted at n<8>, and its ends are connected to a piston n<3> and a spring. To the centre of the long arm is pivoted a forked bar n<7> engaged by a stop on a spoke f. Further, a stop e' is provided for a spoke. The bell-crank levers e are pivoted centrally on rods u<1>, Fig. D, mounted in the body. The inner ends are connected by sliding tangential links c', c<2>, c<3> to the wheels. The outer ends are pivoted to brackets v<8>, which have rounded faces resting on the inner surface of the rim t. The brackets are pivoted laterally to clamps v<7> engaging the notched sides of the rim. Riveted to the clamps v<7> through a flexible cover j are plates m<1> with inwardly-turned edges which hold india-rubber block tyres m. The plate is formed with a central boss v<1>, and the block is further held by a screw v<3> passing through an embedded plate v<2>. The aperture of the plate and the screw are locked by means of serrations. Fitted in a groove in each block is a chain v<6>, the ends of which are respecively looped over, and hooked to, eyes fixed to the end of the plate m<1>. The wheel body consists of spokes r<6> stayed by plates r<5>. The sides are fitted with disks of metal or celluloid in which are panels removable for inspection of the interior. Stops e<4>, e<5>, e<6> are provided for the lever e and rim. In order to increase the spring resistance when the vehicle turns a corner, a block x<3>, Fig. 9, carried by a spring-controlled lever x<4> is thrown across the wheel and jams between a bar x and the end of the lever b, so as to put the spring s<2> out of action.

A heavy duty doctor apparatus effective for creping for use with a roll, for example, a Yankee cylinder. The apparatus features a doctor pressure plate assembly which has a pressure plate adapted to extend the width of the cylinder carried by an array of spaced apart pressure fingers. Each finger has a transverse fulcrum and pairs of jaws provided with opposed surfaces defining between them a registering receiving slot extending from a root to a mouth. The pressure plate is mounted on one of the opposed surfaces, preferably with a pressure pad intervening the pressure plate and surface. The pressure plate projects beyond its mounting surface. The slot also accommodates a blade seat which rests on the other opposed surface and has an abutment adapted to engage the trailing edge of the blade seat which is sandwiched between the pressure plate and blade seat. Each slot is stepped inwards at its root to provide a retaining groove for the blade seat. A preferred finger is of integral solid metal construction. A preferred form of blade seat is an elongated plate of non-metallic heat-resistant material having one surface for resting on the fingers and the opposite surface for receiving the blade and having a protruding bar for engaging the trailing edge of the doctor blade.

column12: NARROW AISLE LIFT TRUCK STEERING SYSTEM.
column13: A narrow aisle lift truck has hydraulic control of steering with means to prevent oversteer by reaction between the wheels and the ground. When steering left, hydraulic fluid flows via line A to the motor and exhausts from the motor through the opposite line B and via a relief valve F which is opened by the pressure in line A. When the steering angle remains constant there is no pressure in A and valve F is closed so that any forces tending to deflect the steering either way are resisted by the one-way flow valves in line A and the closed relief valve F. Bypass C, D are arranged to open under excess pressure so that in the event of for example accidental impact raising the pressure in one or other line the appropriate relief valve opens and this guards against damage to the circuit.

column13: A variable stall speed control device is used with a torque converter of an automatic transmission of an engine for improving the stall speed property of a mechanical power transmission torque converter. The variable stall speed control device includes a lubricating fluid flow housing (4) having one or more internal fluid routing pathways connected to a lubricating fluid reservoir(3). The housing has a fluid inlet (14) and one or more fluid outlets (11) (12) (13) (15). The internal fluid volume of the housing (4) has a connector (11) connected to the torque converter (6) for regulating fluid flow between the housing (4) and the torque converter (6). The internal fluid volume of the housing (4) has a controllable fluid-flow drain (12) (13) for reducing fluid pressure, respectively, in the fluid-flow connector (11) and in the torque converter (6). The controllable fluid-flow drain has a controllable valve therein and an internal fluid routing pathway governed by the controllable valve for controllably and selectively draining torque converter lubricating fluid from the torque converter (6) for producing controlled intermittent on demand pressure reduction in the lubricating fluid within the torque converter (6) by diverting a flow of lubricating fluid from the fluid-flow connector (11) to the drain means (13) to relieve adverse pressure therewithin. A conical electromagnetic horn has an oval cross-section in a plane at right angles to its central axis. column12: Four wheel steering of road vehicles
column13: Mechanism for automatic all wheel steering of a road vehicle comprises an arrangement of gears which move the wheels to the required steering position. The gears are engaged first by a follower set when the steering wheel is operated by the driver. The gears then move, by a worm drive, the leading wheels of the vehicle into the required curve position and when the position is attained the follower disengages the gear. A second follower is connected to the front wheels and as they move engages another set of gears so that the rear wheels are set to an equal curvature as the front but in an angle opposite to that of the front in respect to the line of the vehicle and this follower disengages this gear as this position is attained. The rate of drive to both sets of gears is made variable and proportional to the angle of steering set by the driver so that the steering set of the wheels is attained in the same travel distance for all circles of steering and the gears and worm drive will be arranged so that this distance is the same as that between the leading and trailing wheels. <IMAGE>

column12: Improvements in, and relating to Wheels for Vehicles
column13: 23,058. Brown, F. W. Oct. 18. Wheels with two or more rims or tyres side by side; securing on and detaching from axles; tyres, elastic other than pneumatic. - Relates to the type of wheel described in Specifications Nos. 19,592 and 23,755, A.D. 1905, in which twin wheels are placed side by side in a framework fixed to the main axle. Each revolves on a separate axle supported by springs, and they are connected by a coupling so that they move up and down independently but rotate together. According to the present invention, the periphery of each wheel is a convex curve alternately of less and greater curvature, and the two wheels are so arranged that the prominent parts t, Fig. A of one wheel come opposite to the flatter-parts v of the other. The treads t are of iron, wood, or hard india-rubber ; the parts v are of soft elastic material, and may be hollow or stuffed with a soft core ; the parts v<1> are of intermediate hardness. The wheel is fitted. with a metal rim r, Fig. E, and projections r' are brazed to it to hold the treads t fixed within plates r<2> secured by radial bolts r<3>. The part v may be held by a steel plate or band r<4>, Fig. F, or may be cemented, and may be recessed on its periphery. Each wheel has preferably four treads t, although there may be five or six. In the form shown in Fig. J, axles a<4>, a<5> are supported by bars a<6> separated from the frameworkf by springs s<1>, s<2>, Fig. K, and connected thereto by bars m<5> giving parallel motions in vertical alinement, and by others attached to horizontal arms on the bars a<6>. These bars may be replaced by pin-and-slot connexions. The axle a<4> is formed with an inner flange holding the wheel on ball bearings, and is screwed into a boss on the bar a<6> so as to be removable. The wheels are coupled by an Oldham coupling placed centrally, as also are the disks w<5>, w<6>, as described in the above-mentioned Specification. The axle a<1> carries ordinary carriage springs s, and is bent up and over at a<12> so as to rest on the frame f. Plates f<1> connect the axle to rods f<2> diverging to the frame. The mud guard g is bent to the form shown to accommodate the part a<12>. Figs. G and H show the arrangement of a steering- wheel, in which the end of the axle a<12> is pivoted to the centre of the top of the frame, and the plates f hold a pivot engaging the centre of the bar u linked to the centres of the ends of the frame. The bar u<1> is continued across the front of the vehicle to the corresponding part of the other frame ; or, as shown, a bar u<4> may be added, the object being to enable the frame to turn about a centre u<3> under the pivot a<12>. The steering- mechanism may be attached to the bar u. Preferably, springs s<1>, Fig. K, are used in combination with the springs s<2>. In the arrangement shown in Fig. 5, two toggle levers e<2>, pivoted to the bar a<6> and frame, press the blocks e apart as the bar rises. As shown in Fig. K, the bar is pivoted to the toggle lever e<2>, which is pivoted to the frame and to a rod e<3>, pivoted to the frame through a link e<1> and to a plate pressing on the spring. Fig. N shows a similar arrangement in which the lever e<3> is pivoted at one end to the framework. Fig. L shows the arrangement in the driving-wheel of a bicycle, an Oldham coupling being placed between the wheels w<1>, w<2> and the disks w<3>, w<4>, and chain or belt gearing being used from the crank-axle.

column12: Drying veneer with jets of superheated solvent vapor
column13: Veneer is dried by passing a veneer sheet by at least one set of spaced orifices or nozzles through which jets of superheated organic solvent vapor are directed against one or both of the bottom and top sides of the sheet. After impinging on the wood surface, the spent solvent vapor plus moisture and other volatile substances from the wood passes to a condenser where the solvent is separated and passed to a vaporizer and superheater for recycle to the process. In an optional variation, a preliminary extraction of the entering veneer by condensing solvent is achieved by adjusting the flow rate or temperature of the solvent vapor in the fore part of the drying apparatus. Apparatus for carrying out the veneer drying process with means for recovering and recycling spent solvent is shown.

Improvements in or relating to Apparatus for use in the Production of Oxygen or other Gases.
column13: 21.067. Brown, F., and Stedman, F. J. Oct. 6. Oxygen.-In an apparatus for producing oxygen and other gases by the action of heat on a chemical body, separate charges of the body are moved automatically and successively above the flame. A base-board A has fixed on it guide uprights A', along which run rollers A<4> connected to a second board A', rising and falling as the collapsable gas bag B, which is provided with a central rubber band B<1>, is filled or emptied with gas. The top board carries the generating-apparatus, consisting of a box C, having at one end a tube C<8>, into which a number of the cartridges or cakes of the chemical are placed, and from the lower part of which they are moved forwards over the lamp D by a cam mounted upon the shaft E. This shaft is operated to move the cam by means of a lever G adjustably mounted upon the shaft, the end of the lever resting upon or in the puide A<7> in such a manner that, as the generating-apparatus rises in consequence of the holder filling with gas, the cam is moved away from the cartridge, a spring H ensuring this movement, while, as the generating-apparatus falls, the lever causes the cam to move inwards and force the next cartridge over the flame. A rod C<12> rests upon the cartridges, and is marked with indicating-numerals, so that the operator can see how many cartridges are still unused. The used cartridges are pushed forwards to the receptacle C<1>. The generated gas passes through the tube C<7> to the gas holder, and leaves the holder by the outlet A<5>. Instead of a cam, a plunger, rack and pinion, lever or levers, spring or springs, or other means may be adopted for feeding the cakes forwards, and the feeding-tube may be differently arranged. The feeding - mechanism may be operated by clockwork or other means.

This invention relates to a doctor blade assembly which is an improvement of the assembly as taught in U.S. Pat. No. 3,859,690, as well as to an improved pressure finger which can be used in the assembly. The improved finger includes a bearing part on which the finger can be pivotably mounted. Extending forwardly of the bearing part are two spaced apart jaws having inner facing surfaces which define, between them, mounting slots for the doctor blade. The inner surfaces comprise a plurality of parallel, spaced, transverse grooves, with respective ones of the grooves in one surface being aligned with respective ones of the grooves in the other surfaces. The aligned grooves form vertical sets of grooves, and all fingers on the assembly are disposed so that respective sets of one finger are aligned with respective sets in all other fingers to define a plurality of transverse channels or passages. A blade stop means is inserted through the channels to provide a definite position for the rear end of the blade, and the stop means can be advanced, in the forward channels, or moved back to the rearward channels, depending on the width of the blade, to insure substantially equal blade frontage.

column13: Un chariot élévateur pour couloirs étroits comporte une commande hydraulique de direction avec des moyens d'interdiction de survirage par réaction entre les roues et le sol. Lors d'un virage à gauche, le liquide hydraulique s'écoule par le conduit A vers le moteur et est évacué du moteur par le conduit opposé B et par une soupape de surpression F qui s'ouvre sous la pression dans le conduit A. Lorsque l'angle de direction reste constant, aucune pression ne règne dans le conduit A, et la soupape F est fermée, de sorte que les efforts éventuels tendant à solliciter la direction d'un côté ou de l'autre sont contrés par les soupapes unidirectionnelles sur le conduit A et par la soupape de surpression fermée F. Les soupapes de dérivation C et D sont agencées pour s'ouvrir de sorte que, dans le cas par exemple où un choc accidentel aurait augmenté la pression dans l'un des deux conduits, la soupape de surpression appropriée s'ouvre, protégeant ainsi le circuit contre tout endommagement.

A vertical take-off and landing aircraft having a wing fitted, in the preferred embodiment, with two nacelles one port and one starboard, each nacelle having two tiltmotors in tandem, one forward and one aft of the wing. A conventional rudder and high set tailplane is fitted or, in another embodiment forward canards or in yet another embodiment the aircraft is a flying wing. 

    Forward tiltmotors can be tilted up past the vertical and the aft pusher tiltmotors can be tilted down past the vertical so that the aircraft can maintain a steep descent with the propeller discs horizontal and a low angle of attack of the wing. 

    Each engine is fitted with a two bladed variable pitch propeller that feathers to stop vertically, other embodiments have cyclic pitch propellers. The tiltmotors, have a sideways cant in the tilted positions to reduce engine side loads in translation. 

    All the tiltmotors are equipped with emergency electric motors that can be used to shift the center of lift in hover and assist in gust control. 

    A small wing is provided with very large flaps that are moved in synchronization with the tiltmotors to allow a clear downdraft and also act as a dive brake. 

    A tricycle undercarriage has long nacelle legs to provide ground clearance for the aft propellers and is equipped with side-load sensors for weathercock control. 

    An auto-pilot controls all phases of flight and has a manual back-up control system. 

    Special programs control weathercock effects on landing and take-off, and operation of the emergency electric motors.

Money-boxes, made preferably in the form of a gasmeter, are provided with devices to record the number of coins inserted and to open automatically when a predetermined number have been inserted. A coin f, Fig. 3, on passing down the shoot b<1>, turns the toothed wheel d through one tenth of a revolution, and so operates the pointer c, Fig. 4. On the tenth coin being inserted, a pawl g engages a wheel h with ten teeth, mounted on the spindle h' of the pointer c<1>. Hundreds are recorded by the pointer c<2> on the spindle i<1>, which carries a toothed wheel i operated by the pawl h<2> on the spindle h<1>. A spring pawl d<2> prevents the wheel d from being accidentally rotated, and ensures its stopping in the correct position, the wheels h, i being similarly controlled if required. In the arrangement shown, when the hundredth coin is inserted, the projection n<1>, Fig. 5, of the cam n on the spindle h<1> raises the arm m and disengages the catch j from the lid a<1> against the action of the spring l, thus causing the lid to fly open under the influence of a spring, preferably arranged at the hinge.

   An auto-pilot controls all phases of flight and has a manual back-up control system. Special programs control weathercock effects on landing and take-off, and operation of the emergency electric motors.

column12: System of binding all computerized organizational intelligence on a server computer and RDBMS portal software interface tool and methodology
column13: A system of binding organizational intelligence to a server machine EO whereby it is no longer distributed throughout both the client(s) and the server(s) but managed exclusively within the RDBMS. An RDBMS portal software tool possessing analytical and data manipulative functionalities, but by design no organizational intelligence, is installed and configured at an end user computer. A data table and stored procedure are created in the RDBMS. The table serves registry and coordination functions, while the stored procedure functions as a menu procedure. The tool is the common interface for all stored procedures and for the user. The user passes instructions to the tool, and the tool passes instructions to the RDBMS to execute stored procedures. The tool receives back from the RDBMS the data sets which results from their execution and provides them to the user. The user may manipulate the data and perform analyses using the tool.

column13: A computer-enabled method and related system for allowing market survey contributors to provide their relevant market information and to access that information and the information of others in the same market. The system includes an information database, a query library and a computer program to query the database and evaluate and report on the database information in response to a query. Rules are set to deny access to information not provided by a contributor and to deny access to information with an insufficient number of contributors and/or number of points of data.

column12: Current interrupter for a power network
column13: A current interrupter for use in the power transmission and distribution industry that uses an electrically conductive handle to route current through the current interrupter when the current interrupter shunts current away from opening electrical switch contacts. The electrically conductive handle eliminates the previously used dedicated electrical contacts. The current interrupter has a spring, known as a charging spring, to enhance its opening sequence. The charging spring in conjunction with the guide springs in the interrupter provides an added opening force allowing the internal contacts of the current interrupter to open faster, thus reducing the amount of internal arcing experienced by the current interrupter. The interrupter has a driving bracket a portion of which is electrically conductive. As the handle moves along the conductive portion of the driving bracket, the contacts remain closed even as the handle approaches that point on the bracket past which the contacts will separate.

column12: Improvements in and relating to the treatment of fabrics
column13: Fabrics containing at least 50% of cellulose are impregnated with a reaction product of at least 2.5 mols. of formaldehyde, 1 mol. of urea and at least 1 mol. of glyoxal and are heated in the presence of an acid catalyst. The molecular proportion of formaldehyde to urea may be as much as 4 to 1. The urea and formaldehyde may be reacted first and the product reacted with the glyoxal or the monourein formed by reacting urea and glyoxal (from which glyoxal diurein and impurities have been removed) may be reacted with formaldehyde, or the components may be reacted together simultaneously. The impregnating liquor may have a pH of 6 to 8. Catalysts specified are tartaric and boric acids and magnesium and ammonium di-hydrogen phosphates. The resin may be formed in an atmosphere of superheated steam or the fabric may be treated with steam after resin formation. The fabric may be embossed, glazed, creased or otherwise mechanically treated before forming the resin. The fabric may be composed wholly or partly of cotton, linen or regenerated cellulose and may be subjected subsequently to a swelling or shrinking treatment with caustic soda, as described in Specification 437,361, and may then be further treated with a resin, which may also be a resin from at least 2.5 mols. of formaldehyde, 1 mol. of urea and at least 1 mol. of glyoxal. In Example (3) (B), a stearamidomethylol melamine softener is added to the treating solution. Specification 744,991 also is referred to.ALSO:A resin (formed in situ upon cellulosic textiles) is formed from at least 2.5 mols. of formaldehyde, 1 mol. of urea and at least 1 mol. of glyoxal. Resin formation is promoted by heating in the presence of an acid catalyst, tartaric and boric acids and ammonium and magnesium di-hydrogen phosphates being specified. Textile impregnating solutions have a pH of 6 to 8 and may comprise a reaction product formed by reacting the components simultaneously, or by first reacting the urea with the formaldehyde and subsequently reacting the product with glyoxal or by reacting the monourein obtained from urea and glyoxal (from which glyoxal diurein and other impurities are removed) with formaldehyde. Molecular proportions of up to 4 of formaldehyde to 1 of each of the other components are specified. The examples describe the formation of resin-containing impregnating solutions. In Example (5) a crystallized glyoxal monourein having a melting point of 146 DEG C. is obtained from glyoxal and urea and is dissolved in a formaldehyde solution to which calcium hydroxide is added to give a pH of 8.3. After standing, calcium is precipitated by adding oxalic acid until a pH of 7 is obtained. The solution is then warmed to precipitate calcium oxalate and magnesium dihydrogen phosphate (catalyst) is added to provide a textile treating solution.

The present invention relates to a method of displaying a document in a graphical user interface comprising: displaying in a scrollable manner a first part of the document; displaying a second part of the document; detecting an overlap between the first part and the second part of the document; and displaying in a scrollable manner a consolidated view of the first part and the second part of the document in response to the detecting. The present invention also provides a method of displaying a document in a graphical user interface comprising: displaying in a scrollable manner a first part of the document; displaying a second part of the document; detecting an overlap between the first part and the second part of the document, wherein the first part is comprised in the second part; and removing the second part displayed in response to the detecting. The present invention also provides a method of generating a representation of a position of at least two parts of a document on a scroll bar, comprising: displaying in a first pane a first part of the document and in a second pane, a second part of the document; displaying the scroll bar; locating a first position of the first part in the document, and a second position of the second part in the document; determining a first slider position according to the first position and a length of the scroll bar, and a second slider position according to the second position and the length of the scroll bar; displaying the first slider according to the first slider position in the scroll bar; and displaying the second slider according to the second slider position in the scroll bar.

column12: A METHOD OF DISPLAYING A DOCUMENT
column13: The present invention relates to methods of displaying a document in a graphical user interface wherein a redundancy of information comprised within overlapping views of the document is exploited to reduce a number of panes displayed. The present invention also provides a method of displaying a document in a graphical user interface wherein users operating in a view of the document are provided with an automatic generation and positioning of views of the document comprising complementary information. The present invention also provides a method of generating a representation of at least two parts of a document on a scroll bar whereby a relative positioning of the at least two parts is clearly indicated.

column12: A process and reactor for the pyrolysis of a hydrocarbon feedstock.
column13: Process and apparatus for pyrolysis of a heavy hydrocarbon feedstock in which the feedstock is counter-currently contacted with a hot hydrogenating gas stream flowing spirally from the periphery of a substantially circular reactor (1). The hydrocarbon feedstock is injected through an inlet (4) located toward the centre of reactor (1). The hot hydrogenating gas is preferably formed by combustion, using a steam-oxygen mixture injected through inlet (2), of carbonaceous by-products from the pyrolysis. Product is removed centrally through outlet (3).

column12: High power phased array antenna system and method with low power switching
column13: A module having a first coupler for directing power from a source to first and second paths; a first amplifier disposed in the first path; a second amplifier disposed in the second path; and a second coupler for combining the outputs of the first and second amplifiers. In a more specific implementation, the module further includes a switch connected to the first coupler. The switch is a single-pole double throw switch. Each coupler is a 90-degree coupler that provides the combined energy output by each amplifier to a first or a second output port based on the position of the switch. The first coupler has first and second inputs, each input connected to a throw of the switch. The inclusion of a variable phase shifter allows for the module to be used to drive an element of a phased array antenna. For high power applications, multiple such inventive modules may be used to drive the elements of one or more phased arrays, pointed in different directions, to provide a desired coverage pattern. In this application, each module is adapted to switch energy at low power levels to drive one or more apertures at high power levels. The modules can also be configured as receive only or with circulators as transmit/receive modules. The inventive method provides a technique for switching power at high levels to and from phase array and other antennas and a technique for providing area coverage using multiple phase array antenna arrangements.

column12: APPARATUS AND METHOD FOR IMAGE PROCESSING INCLUDING ONE-DIMENSIONAL CLEAN APPROXIMATION
column13: An apparatus (10) and method for real-time reduction of noise components from echographic images. A plurality of scan line processor circuits (22) are connected through an interface (18) to an echographic imaging apparatus (20), such as an ultrasonic imaging device. Each scan line processor circuit (22) receives a row of dirty image signals (24) and simultaneously and independently performs a one-dimensional side lobe subtraction of noise components (a deconvolution of the dirty beam pattern) from the row of signals using a CLEAN algorithm. After subtraction, the resulting clean components are convolved by the scan line processor circuits (22) with a clean beam pattern to smooth the image for display. Finally, the clean image signals optionally can be masked by a masking multiplier (52) to remove processing artifacts and compressed by a compression device (56) to enhance contrast. The resulting masked and compressed clean image signals (26) are then displayed on a display device (17, 20). A sufficient number of scan line processor circuits (22), relative to the number of rows in a complete image frame, are provided to effect real-time processing of image frames.

column12: A current interrupter for a power network
column13: A current interrupter for use in the power transmission and distribution industry that uses an electrically conductive handle (140) to route current through the current interrupter when the current interrupter shunts current away from opening electrical switch contacts. The electrically conductive handle eliminates the previously used dedicated electrical contacts. The current interrupter has a spring (29), known as a charging spring, to enhance its opening sequence. The charging spring in conjunction with the guide springs in the interrupter provides an added opening force allowing the internal contacts of the current interrupter to open faster, thus reducing the amount of internal arcing experienced by the current interrupter. The interrupter has a driving bracket a portion of which is electrically conductive. As the handle moves along the conductive portion of the driving bracket, the contacts remain closed even as the handle approaches that point on the bracket past which the contacts will separate.

A method, apparatus, and article of manufacture obtain user input during a playback of a macro. A series of user actions are recorded in the form of a macro. A representation of the user actions is displayed. The representation provides nodes that each represent the user actions. One of the nodes is selected and configured by the user to request additional user input relating to a parameter of the selected node during playback of the macro. The macro is played back and automatically pauses at the selected node. User input is obtained and the macro automatically continues execution utilizing the user input for the parameter of the selected node. Additionally, one or the user actions includes a selection of objects. As part of the recorded macro, references to the selected objects are stored in a non-graphical manner. During playback, objects are selected based on the stored references.

column13: The invention provides for controlling operation of systems of a vehicle. The control system 300 comprises controllers configured to: receive 304 image data representative of a user or driver's face; receive 302 audio data from an audio input means within the vehicle; analyse 306 the received audio data to identify a spoken command from the driver; analyse 308 the received image data to determine a contextual meaning (e.g. emotional state) associated with the spoken command; determine 310 a supplemented spoken command in dependence on the spoken command and the contextual meaning; and output 312 an indication of the supplemented spoken command to one or more vehicle control systems in accordance with the supplemented spoken command. A Facial Action Coding System (FACS) could be used to interpret the facial image. The contextual meaning could include sincerity or insincerity. The system can make a judgement about whether a driver was being sarcastic or jocular when asking certain questions (212).

column13: Embodiments of a switchable high-power transmit module to selectively provide a high-power microwave signal in excess of one kilowatt to one of first and second output paths are disclosed herein. The module includes a switch to receive a lower-power microwave signal from a source, a first ninety-degree coupler for directing power from the switch to first and second paths, a first high-power amplifier disposed in the first path, a second high-power amplifier disposed in the second path, and a second ninety-degree coupler to receive output signals of the first and second amplifiers. The switch is configured to selectively couple the lower-power microwave signal between first and second input ports of the first ninety-degree coupler. When the switch couples the lower-power microwave signal to a selected one of the input ports of the first coupler, signals generated by the first and second high-power amplifiers are combined in the second ninety-degree coupler to provide the high-power microwave output signal on only one of the output paths.

column12: Improvements in or relating to telecommunication exchanges
column13: 1,146,957. Automatic telephone exchanges. STANDARD TELEPHONES & CABLES Ltd. 5 May, 1967, No. 20922/67. Heading H4K. A subscriber who wishes future calls to him to be diverted at the exchange to a predetermined other subscriber first dials from his own subset for a common transfer circuit and on receiving second dial tone or a proceed to send signal dials in a digit identifying the other subscriber. The transfer circuit transmits a signal back over the network to the line circuit of the calling subscriber which enables a socalled subscriber's transfer circuit associated with the calling subscriber's line, so that as the common transfer circuit offers the identity of the other subscriber to all subscriber's transfer circuits belonging to lines having the transfer facility the identity is only registered in the calling subscriber's transfer circuit currently being enabled. A particular relay is thereby operated in this transfer circuit, which relay self holds when the enablement signal ceases and which disconnects the subscriber's outlet of the final selector or switching stage and connects it to the line of the other subscriber. A calling subscriber receives transfer tone when the other subscriber's identity is set in the transfer circuit and he then hangs up. To end the transfer arrangement a subscriber sends a cancellation signal to the common transfer circuit which then operates a relay in the subscriber's transfer circuit which releases the operated relay, release being delayed if a transferred call is in progress. The transfer facility is described with reference to a cross-bar exchange and a step-by-step mechanical switching exchange.

column13: 26,009. Brown, A., Lomax, H., and Lomax, F. Nov. 28. Stoppers; refilling, preventing.-A bottle or like vessel for containing spirits &c. is formed with two seats b, c for the valves d, e, and with a bridge-piece h below the seat c. The valve d has a stem f, which passes through a central aperture in the valve e, and through an aperture in the bridge-piece h. The valve d is secured by two spring-pressed or pivoted arms or spurs, such as i, Fig. 7, which fold up to permit the insertion of the stem f through the bridge-piece, and then open out, as shown. The bridge-piece is closed on its underside, to prevent the entrance of liquid through the central hole, and to protect the liquid from contact with the metal of the valves &c. The valve d is formed with a boss d<x>, Fig. 5, which limits the movement of the valve e, and the valve e has a boss e<x>, Fig. 6, which enters a recess in the bridge h. The valves permit the liquid to be poured out, but prevent refilling. In a modification, the distance between the valves is increased. The bridge h is preferably made integral with the neck of the vessel, but it may consist of a metal or other plug k, Fig. 9, inserted in the neck, and secured in the same manner as the stem f.

Board games. - Relates to boards for playing games, and consists in making the board and pieces of flexible material, in order that they may be rolled or folded up, and in fitting the board and pieces with male and female members of a press-button or similar fastening to prevent displacement of the pieces. The board u, Figs. 1 and 2, is made of leather, leather cloth, or other flexible material, and is provided either with one element e of a pressbutton fastening or is perforated. Stopping pipes. - Relates to apparatus, more particularly applicable for stopping drain pipes for testing purposes, and consisting of an ex. pansible bag, shown in longitudinal section in Fig. 1. A cylindrical india-rubber bag A is closed at one end and attached at the other to a flanged pipe B. Surrounding the bag is the cylindrical canvas cover C, the diameter of which corresponds with that of the pipe to be stopped. column12: An Improved Signalling Device for use in connection with Colliery Winding Engines.
column13: 118,248. Davies, A. E., and Brown, F. M. April 6, 1918. Order apparatus; mine signalling systems. - An electrically-operated signalling device for use in connexion with colliery winding engines comprises a magnet 1 and a solenoid 2 both in the same circuit which is closed by a switch 4 operated by hand or by the pull rope. A pointer 8 is loosely mounted on a fixed axle 11 and is connected to a ratchet wheel 7 provided with a stop 9 and spring controlled so as normally to bring the stop 9 against a stop 10 on the axle 11. A second solenoid 13 has a core 15 which, when the ratchet wheel 7 is moved by a pawl 6 on a lever 5 attracted by the magnet 1, falls in between the stops 9, 10, and prevents the pointer 8 returning to zero till the solenoid 13 is excited by the closing of its circuit by starting of the engine or by hand. The solenoid 2 has a cross-bar 18 on its plunger 17 which is controlled in its fall by a dash-pot 21. A projection 23 on the cross-bar 18 trips a lever 24 when rising and lifts a retaining pawl 26, and by a pin 27 thereon also the actuating pawl 6, clear of the wheel 7, thus allowing the pointer to fall back to the No. 1 indication. The parts are designed so that, on closing the switch 4, the wheel 7 is moved one tooth before the projection 23 rises to lift the pawls 6, 26, and when this occurs immediately afterwards the core 15 has already fallen to prevent return of the wheel 7 and pointer 8 to zero. Subsequent closings of the switch 4 belonging to the same signal will take place before the projection 23 has time to fall below the trip lever 24, and so are recorded. In the event of the signal not being answered, sufficient time will have elapsed before it is considered necessary to repeat the signal for the projection 23 to fall below the lever 24, and on making the first contact of the repetition the pointer will be released to fall back to the No. 1 position and subsequent contacts will be added on as before. Starting of the engine, or otherwise, excites the solenoid 13 and raises the core 15 and with it a hooked &c. rod 28 which lifts the pawls 6, 26, so allowing the pointer to return to zero. The ratchet wheel 7 may be geared to the pointer 8 to increase the movement of the latter. A series of lamps may be used to give the signal, and rotary contacts are described whereby lamps are successively lit, the earlier ones in the series either being extinguished or remaining lit as the signal proceeds.

TREATMENT OF KLEBSIELLA PNEUMONIAE WITH LIPOSOMALLY FORMULATED GLUTATHIONE
column13: The invention proposes routine treatment of patients, particularly those admitted to an ICU, with Vitamin D and liposomal glutathione for prophylaxis and treatment against Group B Streptococcus and Carbapenem-resistant enterobacteriaceae, and biomarkers to measure effectiveness of treatment. Further, because the method of treatment bolsters body defenses as well as appearing to have direct killing action, the propensity to create more and more antibiotic- and/or carbapenem resistant strains is downgraded.

This invention relates to a composition, the use of a composition for treatment, and a method of treatment of infection with Respiratory syncytial virus (RSV). The composition for treatment is a liposomally formulated reduced glutathione in a therapeutically effective amount to decrease the growth of respiratory syncytial virus. An oral preparation of liposomal reduced glutathione and a powdered form that can be reconstituted with sterile water or saline for intravenous administration are described.

column13: A fertilizer containing tri-calcium phosphate is made by heating an alumino-phosphate rock with calcium sulphate and carbonaceous material (coal, coke or anthracite) at a temperature of about 1100 DEG C. or higher. The reaction mixture contains 2 to 7 mols. CaO per mol. of P2O5. The aluminium phosphate is converted to calcium phosphate, and the aluminium sulphate formed is reduced to give sulphur and/or sulphur dioxide. The sulphur released may be recovered in elemental form by admitting an inert gas, e.g. nitrogen, or as sulphur dioxide by blowing in air or oxygen. In examples, alumino-phosphate rock (e.g. wavellite from Senegal), coal and calcium sulphate (preferably hemi hydrate) are mixed in proportions of 3.3 mols. CaO and 3 mols. coal per mol. of P2O5, and the mixture ground to 85 mesh. The mixture is then granulated with steam and dried at 60 DEG to 80 DEG C. The granulated product, of about 6 mesh, is then heated in a muffle furnace or rotating kiln to 1050 DEG to 1150 DEG C. in an atmosphere of nitrogen for 1 hour. The sulphur and gases are collected, and the product treated with steam at 1200 DEG to 1400 DEG C. to remove fluorine. The calcium sulphate used may consist of waste gypsum obtained in the processing of other phosphate rock as a filter cake which is dried at 125 DEG C. and ground.

column12: Improvements in or relating to electric signal storage and re-transmission circuits
column13: 658,948. Automatic exchange systems. STANDARD TELEPHONES & CABLES, Ltd. Nov. 16, 1949, No. 29310. [Class 40 (iv)] In a keysender, digits are set up on groups of static electrical switches and transferred automatically one after another as complements to a binary counter comprising pairs of static electrical switches, the digits then being counted out by the counter. Start key KST energizes relay ST to apply anode potential to the cold cathode storage tubes AT1-4, RT1-4, &c. and to the even tubes of a counting chain CRT1-8, a pulse network PN1 firing the even tubes of the counter. Depression of a digit key KO-9 applies positive potential from contact st2 to leads connected by rectifiers to the trigger electrodes of one or a combination of the storage tubes AT1-4, BT1-4, &c. according to a code, the potential being blocked by the rectifiers except in the case of the first set of storage tubes AT1-4, which receives a pulse from the point P1 in response to the operation of a sequential operation distributing circuit (not shown) actuated by depression of the first digit key. The related storage tubes fire, and in like manner the other digits are set up on subsequent groups of storage tubes. When storage is complete, depression of start send key KSS energizes DS to ionize all storage tubes in the group following that used for the last digit, if all groups have not been used. Release of key KSS energizes relay DSR, which restores the sequential operation distributing circuit (not shown) and connects anode potential to the odd tubes of the counter CRT1-8. DSR also releases DS to cause the distributing circuit to apply a positive pulse to point P1 to cause all inert tubes in the first storage group to fire and pass positive pulses to ionize the related odd tubes in the counting chain, which operates on the binary system so that the complement with respect to 16 of the digit is entered. Operation of counting chain. Ionization of an odd tube extinguishes the associated even tube. Transfer of any digit fires either CRT5 or CRT7 to cause pulse network PN2 to fire tube TRT and energize TR, which operates IG when impulse springs A open. IG operates IP, which via pulse network PN1 applies positive pulses to the first pair of tubes in the counter as pulses go out over contacts B, the counter responding in known manner until all even tubes are ionized, when CRT8 fires tube SZT to operate SZ. Relay IG then falls back to stop the impulses at ig2, and by means not shown actuates the sequential operation circuit so that the second digit is transferred and transmitted in similar manner. Release' of IG also applies positive potential over a time delay network to fire tube IDT so extinguishing tube SZT and releasing SZ. After the last digit is transmitted, an attempt to transmit a non-existent digit fails because neither CRT5 not CRT7 is ionized and release of SZ operates CL to light the finish send lamp, start key KST is released and the sender returns to normal. The invention may be applied to registers and may use thermistors, hard tube trigger circuits, cathode-ray tubes or transistons instead of the gas-filled tubes.

Vucuum cleaning-apparatus; bellows.-Relates particularly to that class supported by two or more wheels and adapted to be moved backwards and forwards on the carpet or similar surface, the bellows of the apparatus being operated from the wheels. For cleaning upholstery, a hand nozzle is coupled to the suction pipe, the floor nozzle being held out of action. The light supporting - frame a, mounted on the wheels, carries the handle 4 and bail 5. The wheels carry crank - pins 6, Fig. 1, to which are coupled links 7 so that motion is transmitted to a cross-bar working in slots 9. The bellows p are secured to the crossbar and are opened and closed as the cross-bar reciprocates. The forward end carries the dustremoving chamber d, which may have a hemispherical lower end and a removable cover c. The dust chamber contains a removable canvas bag to receive the dust from the suction nozzle g, which may be supported on the arm h pivoted in such a way that the nozzle adapts itself to inequality in the carpet, the flexible hose j also assisting in this movement. To adjust the nozzle laterally, it is made in two parts, pivoted together and adjustable by means of a bolt and nut and slot connexion. To secure the leather of each of the bellows to the corresponding end disk or plate r, the disk is beaded over at its edge to allow the leather q to curl over and to be secured by semicircular hollow clamps s, the ends of the enveloping clamps being secured by bolts which pass through tightening-up lugs. The outlet valve passage u of each bellows is larger in area than the inlet t. The adjacent ends of the bellows are connected by a bolt and boss connexion v. The front air chamber w communicates with the dust chamber d through apertures x which are protected by an inner screen y. The front and rear air chambers are connected by the air passage 2, and each communicates with the inlet air valves t. The bellows are enclosed by the casing 3. Fig. 4 shows a modification in which the disks of the bellows are made of wood, with grooved edges in which the leather is secured by wire rings 19 with couplings 20. The connecting air passage 2 in this case supports the disks through a sliding sleeve 21, a distance-piece 22 preserving the space between the bellows. Motion is communicated to the bellows from the rear wheels b through crankpins 6, links 7, studs 24, bowls 25, and links 26. Front wheels are dispensed with, so that substantially the whole weight of the apparatus tends to keep the nozzle g on the floor. The dust chamber d is arranged horizontally, the cover c being at the front end and secured by clips 13. The cover is formed with the passage 14 preferably elongated to admit of lateral shifting of the nozzle.

column13: The present invention comprises a light fixture including a housing, a light source, means to secure a light source to the housing, a lens and a reflector. The reflector and lens are positioned so as to direct light from the light source onto an unlit side of the housing. The light fixture is normally suspended from the ceiling or attached to a wall. A greater portion of the light from the light source is reflected off the ceiling or wall, whereas a smaller portion of the light from the light source is reflected off the reflector and onto the housing. After the smaller portion is reflected off the housing, the smaller portion and the larger portion are traveling in generally the same direction, thereby reducing the contrast between the housing and the ceiling or wall. The present fixture housing is very shallow, preferably less than about 3" deep. It includes one or more side rails, with each side rail being utilized to reflect the light from the light source onto the housing with a first reflector and to alter other diffuse lighting characteristics with a lens, perforated metal, or a second reflector.

column12: Managing Metadata for External Content within a Computing Environment
column13: Technologies are described for managing metadata associated with external content. For example metadata can be obtained that describes content stored on external systems. The metadata can be obtained without locally storing the content items themselves. For example, the metadata can be retrieved from the external systems while the external content continues to be stored on the external systems. The metadata can also include indications of the actions that can be performed in relation to the external content. For example, actions can be obtained (e.g., locally determined and/or obtained from the external systems) and added to the metadata. The metadata can be stored and used locally. For example, the metadata can be used to locally perform the actions in relation to the external content. The metadata can also be used to locally initiate actions that are then carried out in the external systems.

column13: 966,122. Hydrogen diffusion elements. JOHNSON, MATTHEY & CO. Ltd. March 8, 1963 [April 17, 1962], No. 14810/62. Heading B1L. [Also in Division F2] A hydrogen diffusion element comprises a tube of hydrogen-permeable material in which is located so as to extend along the bore thereof, at least one stiffener whose lateral rigidity is retained under stress of temperature and pressure thus preventing deformation of the tube but permitting passage of hydrogen. The tube may be made of Pd or Pd alloy, e.g. 25% Ag-Pd. The stiffener which may be made of stainless steel or nickel, may be an elongated coil spring, a twisted metal tape, a perforated tube, a plurality of metallic or ceramic rods, a multiplicity of small diameter metal shot or a plurality of intertwined or consecutively arranged wires or tapes. A pervious ceramic rod or tube may also be used as a stiffener and the rod may have a diameter less than the internal diameter of the diffusion tube and be carried by a header mounted in the open end of the diffusion tube. A hydrogen diffusion apparatus, Fig. 2, is constructed out of a number of these diffusion elements 1 closed at one end 2 and containing stiffener springs 3. The tubes are mounted in the base 6 of a cup 5. Gaseous mixtures containing hydrogen enter under pressure at 4d and pass along the tube 4b and into the casing 4. Hydrogen diffuses into the interior of the tubes 1 and passes out through 8. The remaning gas passes out from the apparatus at 4e. In specific embodiments, various temperatures and pressures are exemplified in relation to a stainless steel coil, the highest values being 700 ‹C. and 800 p.s.i.g. respectively. The Provisional Specification discloses the use of glass beads as stiffeners.

column12: Improvements in or relating to the cooling of aircraft propulsion plants
column13: 720,012. Gas turbine plant. BRISTOL AEROPLANE CO., Ltd. April 23, 1952 [April 23, 1951], No. 9442/51. Class 110 (3). [Also in Group XXXIV] A gas turbine plant burning liquid fuel has means for circulating liquid fuel in a circuit in heat exchange relation with parts requiring heating and cooling respectively and means for replenishing the fuel in the circuit with fresh fuel from the fuel storage means to make up for normal losses of fuel from the circuit and to prevent the return of fuel to the storage means. Fuel from a tank 5 is supplied by a booster pump 6 to the main engine fuel pump 9 through a filter 7. Fuel is bled from the conduit between the filter 7 and pump 9 and passed through a non-return valve 10, a heat exchanger 13 and a chamber 11 for separating the air and vapour from the fuel to a further pump 17. The fuel is heated in the heat exchanger 13 by the hot lubricating oil from the engine. The valve 10 closes in the flow direction if the flow exceeds a predetermined amount. The flow of hot fuel from the pump 17 is divided into three paths 19, 20 and 21. One path 19 passes through the heating jacket of the filter before joining the inlet of the heat exchanger 13 at 23. The other two paths 20, 21 pass to two annular distributing chambers 24, 25 disposed around the air intake to the compressor 27. From the chamber 25, the fuel flows through the guide blades 28 to another annular chamber 29 and from thence into the jacket space 30 of a doublewalled intake bullet fairing 31. The fuel flows from the chamber 24 through spaces 32 of the leading edge fairings 33 of the intake spider to the space 30. The combined flow from the space 30 passes through the space 35 of a hollow intake spider arm and the conduit 36 to the point 23. To control the rate of heat transfer throttle valves 37, 38 are provided, these valves may be controlled by manual, thermostatic or ice-detecting means. When thermostatic control is provided, the thermostat may be placed in the heating or cooling part of the engine, depending on which is the more critical. Additional heat exchangers 39, 40 may be employed. These heat exchangers may use hot gas as a heating medium or may bring the fuel into contact with the hot external or internal parts of the engine. In this case, the heat exchanger 13 may be omitted. There is a possibility of the fuel being overheated where additional heat exchangers are used. In this case, some of the hot fuel may be returned to the fuel system through a conduit 41, a throttle valve 42 and a venturi 43 and the valve 10 over-ridden so that it may pass more fuel. The matrix of the heat exchanger 13, the pump 17 and driving motor 18 may be assembled to form a unit which may be mounted on the wall of the lubricating oil storage tank above the oil level. The motor 18 may be a turbine driven by air bled from the compressor. The invention may be applied to a plant with several engines.

column12: MANAGING METADATA FOR EXTERNAL CONTENT WITHIN A COMPUTING ENVIRONMENT
column13: Technologies are described for managing metadata associated with external content. For example metadata can be obtained that describes content stored on external systems. The metadata can be obtained without locally storing the content items themselves. For example, the metadata can be retrieved from the external systems while the external content continues to be stored on the external systems. The metadata can also include indications of the actions that can be performed in relation to the external content. For example, actions can be obtained (e.g., locally determined and/or obtained from the external systems) and added to the metadata. The metadata can be stored and used locally. For example, the metadata can be used to locally perform the actions in relation to the external content. The metadata can also be used to locally initiate actions that are then carried out in the external systems.
