Flue-dust, collecting and removing; draught-inducers.-Relates to means for separating sparks, cinders, dust, &c. from furnace gases by centrifugal action, applicable also for improving the induced draught by rendering it more even in character. Fig. 2 shows the invention applied to a locomotive. The application to refuse destructors is mentioned. The top of the blast pipe 5 and the chimney base 4, or a flared extension thereof 6, are enclosed by a casing 2<a>, which may be shaped as shown or cylindrical throughout, and is preferably in two portions. The gases &c. enter the tangential louvered inlets 7 and receive a circular motion in the casing, the heavier particles being projected to the wall, while the smoke passes out through the chimney 4. An upstanding worm 8 may be provided to facilitate the separation. The dust &c. is led through a pipe 9 and a non-return valve on to the track or elsewhere. When used with a refuse destructbr or other land plant, the casing may be placed in a by-pass flue, the gases being ejected axially to the stack, and the casing may be provided with a water jacket to generate the steam for the blast nozzle.

column12: Method for providing a consumer with information regarding commercial prescription availability and cost
column13: A method is disclosed whereby consumers enrolled in subscribing prescription benefit plans can easily obtain information over the Internet regarding costs and availability of their prescription medications at local and mail-order participating pharmacies of their choice, based on the prescription benefit plans of which they are members. Data on medication dosages, quantities and net costs at a plurality of pharmacies are compiled by the method and presented on-line so that each member of a plan can select the combination of cost and convenience for prescription fulfillment that he or she prefers. The method then allows the user to select prescription fulfillment directly from the selected pharmacy on-line. Other information,.such as general medical, medication and health information can also be made available. Patients, pharmacies, PBMs and plan payers all benefit.

column12: Improvements in or relating to liquid fuel supply systems
column13: 881,002. Filters. ROLLS-ROYCE Ltd. March 12, 1959 [April 3, 1958], No. 10934/58. Class 46. [Also in Group XXVI] A liquid fuel supply system for a gas turbine comprising a fuel filter and downstream of it a unit, e.g. a fuel supply control unit, in which ice formation is liable to cause malfunctioning, has means arranged on sensing of ice formation in the filter, to heat the unit prior to the heating of the filter for de-icing purposes whereby water formed by melting of ice in the filter flows through the unit without freezing therein. Fuel from a tank 16 is delivered by a booster pump 17 into a fuel pipe 18 containing a fuel heater 19 heated by air tapped from the engine compressor 10 by a conduit 20. The air flow is controlled by a valve 21 operated by a solenoid 21a. The fuel leaving the heater 19 normally passes through a valve 29, a main filter 24 high pressure fuel pump 22, control mechanism 25 and shut off cock 26 to the engine. The system also comprises an auxiliary fuel filter 27. When ice clogs the filter 24, the pressure drop across it increases and causes the collapse of the bellows 34 so that switch 35 is closed. This energises the solenoid 21a which opens valve 21 and allows hot air to be supplied to the heater 19. At the same time the motor 31 is operated to rotate cam 30. This allows spring 29b to urge valve member 29a to the left so that fuel is supplied to the control unit 25 through the auxiliary filter 27. After a period of ninety seconds the cam 30 starts to move the valve member 29a to the right so that for about fifteen seconds both filters are fed with heated fuel. Thereafter, fuel is fed to the filter 24 only. During the periods when hot fuel is fed to the filter 24, the ice in the filter is melted and due to the previous heating of the control unit, the resulting water flows through the control mechanism without freezing. The motor 31 also rotates a cam 30a which closes a holding switch 35a for one revolution of the motor. In a modification, Figs. 2 and 3 (not shown), the control unit and filter have control valves and connecting ducting arranged so that in one setting of the valves the heater is arranged between the filter and the control unit and in the second setting, the filter is arranged between the heater and the control unit.

column13: 774,812. Pressure-relieving devices for fluids. JOHNSON, MATTHEY & CO., Ltd. Aug. 9, 1955 [Aug. 30, 1954], No. 25156/54. Class 135. A vacuum support for a domed disc 3 which is adapted to burst on the attainment of a predetermined pressure on the concave side thereof consists of a domed member 2 shaped to fit exactly the member 3 and provided with apertures 5 to allow access of the pressure to the member 3, the member 2 having radial slits 7 so that if, after bursting of the disc 3, the holes 5 present such a resistance to flow as to prevent adequate release of pressure the member 2 opens up to allow unrestricted flow. The member 2 is formed initially with a slightly more domed contour than is required in the finished member so that after the formation of the holes 5 and the radial slits 7 the member can be pressed downwardly to the required shape in which process the edges of the radial slits are pressed into tight engagement with each other. This process is facilitated by the truncating of the apex of each of the sectors 6 formed by the radial slits. A thin piece of foil, e.g. silver, 12, soldered in position, retains the sectors in mutual alignment and ruptures to allow the member 2 to open. An arcuate slit 7a is associated with each radial slit to facilitate bending of the sectors 6. The member 2 may be made, e.g., of nickel.

column12: Apparatus and method for controlling vehicle system operation
column13: A control system/method, for controlling operation of a vehicle system, comprising one or more controllers. The control system determines 306 whether the one or more identified Facial Action Units correspond to Facial Action Units associated with an underlying medical condition and outputs a control signal 308 which is configured to control operation of a vehicle system in dependence on a determination that the one or more identified Facial Action Units correspond to Facial Action Units associated with the underlying medical condition. column12: Improvements in the grain-stabilising of metals and alloys
column13: An improved grain stabilized material consisting of a major proportion of a platinum group metal, or an alloy containing one or more of these metals as a major constituent, and a minor proportion consisting of 0.005% to 5% by weight of the total mixture of a refractory metal carbide is produced by compacting and sintering an intimate mixture of the finely divided constituents. The carbides of W, Mo, Ti, Zr, V, Nb or Ta may be used. The alloy compositions quoted are Pt sponge + 0.2% WC, Pd sponge + 0.2% WC, Pt-8% Ni + 0.2% WC, 70% Pt - 20% Pd - 10% Rh + 0.2% WC. A mixture of 90% Pt and 10% Rh is also referred to. The compacting may be at a pressure of 4-16 tons p.s.i. and the sintering at a temperature of 1100 DEG C.-1300 DEG C. for a period of 20 minutes to two hours in an atmosphere of air, hydrogen or carbon monoxide. The sintered materials may be hot forged at 1000 DEG C. to 1200 DEG C. and cold worked with intermediate annealing at 1000 DEG C.

column12: Improvements in or relating to cable winding apparatus
column13: 953,232. Winches. UNITED KINGDOM ATOMIC ENERGY AUTHORITY. July 3, 1962 [July 10, 1961], No. 24833/61. Heading B8B. [Also in Division G6] A winch for withdrawing a thermo-couple cable from a nuclear reactor channel comprises a cast iron shielding body 1 having a chamber 2 enclosing a cable winding reel 3, an opening 4 to the chamber being normally closed by a door 5 hinged about a pin 6. The reel 3 has a square aperture (Fig. 3, not shown) whereby it is mounted on the square section end portion 9 of a fitting 13, this fitting being keyed to, and slidable in, the hollow end of a shaft 8 driven by a sprocket 22 through a one-way clutch 23. The fitting 13 is connected to a spring-biased spindle 12 having an end 26 engageable by a tool (not shown) whereby pulling on the end 26 causes the end portion 9 to be withdrawn from the reel aperture and the reel to drop through a discharge port 39 after removal of a sliding bolt 40. A drum 75 has wound thereon a compressed gas hose 85a supporting a thermocouple cable cutting device 85 as disclosed in Specification 953,233, this device being received in a vertical passage 52 in the body 1. The passage 52 has a lamp 59 and an observation port (Fig 2, not shown) and is connected to the chamber 2 by a passageway 57. The drum 75 is driven by a handle 76 and rotates the sprocket 22 through a chain 80 and a chain-wheel mounted on the drum axis, the drive to the sprocket including a friction clutch. In use the winch is clamped on a shield box 83 located over a reactor charge tube 84 and the end of a selected thermocouple cable 86 from a fuel element is threaded through the device 85 and the passageway 57 and coiled on the reel 3. The device 85 is lowered by the drum 75 to cut the cable 86 adjacent the fuel element, the clutch 23 preventing rotation of the reel 3. The device 85 is now raised and simultaneously the cable 86 is wound on the reel, the arrangement being such that the cable 86 is wound in faster than the hose 85a so that the cable is wound tightly on the reel, the friction clutch preventing overstressing the cable. When the entire cable is on the reel the winch is transported to a flask where the bolt 40 is withdrawn and the reel discharged thereinto. In another construction (Figs. 7, 8, not shown) for use where the thermocouple has a weakened section as disclosed in Specification 932,264, the drum 75 and device 85 are omitted the handle drives the reel directly.

column13: 699,817. Packing slow combustion fuzes and detonators. IMPERIAL CHEMICAL INDUSTRIES. Ltd. Oct. 17, 1951 [Dec. 22, 1950], No. 31265/50. Class 9(i) [Also in Group IX] Apparatus for packaging safety fuze cord in contiguous flat coils to form a hollow cylinder between end discs with a wrapping of flexible sheet material around the curved surface is shown in Fig. 1. The fuze cords 13 are fed along a tray 2 resting on the inclined surface of a block 1 and pass between upstanding tapered teeth 4 of a comb fitting into a groove in the tray. The sides of the tray converge towards a flexible belt 5 attached to the forward end. On this belt lies a strip 3 of paper or fibre-board. The belt 5 passes over the roller of a tensioning device 6 such as a compression spring or a weight after passing beneath a mandrel consisting of a hollow metal drum 10 having a flange at one end against which rests an annulus: 11. In this annulus is a slot 12 aligned with a recess 14 in the reeling drum. Each fuze cord is attached to a detonator 15 which is placed in the recess-14. A spring clip 8 holds the wrapping strip 3 in position and dowel pins 16 secure the annulus to the flange of the drum. A pair of guide rollers is bolted to the tray and the belt, which is also attached to the block 1. The forward end of the tray is of tapered thickness so that the upper surface of the belt is aligned with the main surface of the tray. The clip 8 is operated by means of a pressure bar 9. As the drum revolves the fuze cords 13 are coiled around it, Fig. 4, a removable recessed disc 17 holding the coils in position. The end disc 17 is slotted similarly to the annulus 11 to facilitate insertion of the detonators into the recess in the drum and is secured to the drum by dowel pins. The drum, which is supported by a bearing 19, is connected to a driving belt 20. On completion of the winding the wrapping 3 is secured by a strip 21 of adhesive material, the package is removed from the drum and end cover discs 22 are attached by strips 23 of adhesive material, Fig. 6.

column13: Technologies are described for managing multi-tenant identifiers (e.g., multi-tenant keys or multi-tenant database keys). Creating multi-tenant identifiers can comprise receiving a source system identifier from a source system, determining a source identity provider of the source system, creating a multi-tenant identifier representing a combination of the source system identifier and the source identity provider, and storing the created multi-tenant identifier. Using multi-tenant identifiers can comprise receiving a request to lookup a source system identifier, associated with a source system, in a multi-tenant identifier mapping table, determining a source identity provider of the source system, identifying an entry in the table with the source system identifier and the source identity provider, and returning a multi-tenant identifier associated with the identified entry in the table.

The waterrepellent substance may be a C 16 -C 20 fatty acid or a water-insoluble salt thereof, a C 16 -C 20 aliphatic amine or a silicone. Specified substances are stearic, palmitic, lauric and oleic acids; calcium, aluminium, magnesium and zinc stearates; calcium and zinc palmitate; aluminium ricinoleate, aluminium oleate, stearylamine and alkyl silicones. The phosphate rock may have a surface area of at least 500 cm.<SP>2</SP>/g. with no particles larger than 0À5 mm. Coating may be by spraying or grinding. Powdered rock may be stored in the open by forming a heap with at least the outside layer consisting of the composition of the invention. The coated rock may be mixed with potassium chloride for use as a fertilizer.

column12: Improvements in or relating to Means or Apparatus for Operating or Controlling Type-writing and Type-setting Mechanism by Means of Perforated Tape.
column13: 25,861. Creed, F. G., Coulsen, W. A., Brown, H. T., and Brown, N. P. Dec. 12. Typewriters; type, setting.-Relates to apparatus of the kind described in Specification No. 22,653, A.D. 1902, for operating typewriting or type-setting mechanism by means of perforated tape. The holes in the tape effect the re-arrangement of a number of sliding combs, each such arrangement permitting a bar to enter the recesses in the combs and connect a key-lever of the machine with an actuating-lever. The tape is guided between two vertical plates a, b, each having ten pairs of holes which coincide with the holes d' in the tape d, Fig. 9. The plates a, b are carried by a frame i, which is reciprocated horizontally by a cam k on the driving-shaft m. A perforated plate p, Fig. 7, secured to one of the plates a, b by a spring, enables the tape-guide to be cleared of any matter that accumulates therein. The feed-holes d<3>in the tape are engaged by a pinwheel r having on its shaft a pinion which can be engaged by a feed-rack sliding in a fixed vertical guide v, Fig. 8. A shutter 17 is held by a spring- actuated lever against the lower end of the feedrack. Opposite to the tape-guide a, b are plates 25 in which slide ten pairs of selector pins 27, each of which actuates one of a number of selector plates 21, pivoted on a vertical rod 22 and held in normal position by springs 24. To each pair of selector plates corresponds a stop plate 20, adapted to be moved by a spring 29 into the guide v in order to arrest the descent of the feed-rack. The horizontally-sliding combs 36 of the typewritercontrolling, mechanism are urged to the right by springs 38, and are controlled by a lever 40 and a cam on thedriving-shaft. The tape is passed up between the plates a, b until the first hole or holes d' comes opposite the top pair of holes in the plates a, b. Then, upon the machine starting, the tapeguide is moved by the cam k towards the pins 27. The pins which are opposite to holes in the tape remain at rest, but pins opposite to blank parts of the tape are moved to the left and displace corresponding selector plates 21. The combs 36, being released by the lever 40, move to the right against a stop, those combs which are opposite to displaced plates 21 being thereby prevented from moving. The blank part d<2> of the tape at the end of each letter causes both plates 21 of the corresponding pair to be displaced and a stop plate 20 to move into the guide v. The plates 21 are retained in their displaced positions by a hooked lever 47 actuated by a cam 49. The forward motion of the tape-guide moves the feed-rack out of gear with its pinion, and the rack is then caused to descend until it meets the displaced stop plate 20. The shutter 17 is thereby moved into. position to arrest all the combs 36 which are below the stop plate 20. The tape-guide is moved back by the cam k, and the feed-rack re-engages the pinion. The rack is then raised by a cam, and the tape is fed upwards to bring the next letter into position. After printing, the combs 36 are retracted by the lever 40 and the stop plate 20 by a rod actuated by a cam. When a blank space in the tape follows the last letter of a word, all the combs move forward until arrested by the shutter 17, except the first pair, which are prevented from moving by displaced selector plates, and a spacing movement of the typewriter is thereby effected. The typewriter-controlling mechanism comprises vertical bars 53, pivoted on a rod 54 and pressed by springs 58 against the combs 36. The bars 53 move hooked rods 63, pivoted to the key-levers 62 of the typewriter, beneath a lever 64 which is actuated by a cam or eccentric on the driving-shaft m. The driving-shaft is provided with a clutch mechanism consisting of a driving-cone 74 on a loose wheel 76, Fig. 6, and a driven cone 75 which can be moved along the shaft by means of a screwed sleeve 78 and spring 79. The clutch is controlled by a pivoted stop 83 actuated by a hand-lever 86. The clutch is automatically disengaged after a certain number of words have been written in a line by means of a cam 96, Fig. 3, which is rotated step by step from the lever 64. A bar 104 is pivoted on a shaft 105, carried by a lever frame 106 which is connected to the clutch stop 83. The bar 104 is vibrated by the bar 53 which actuates the typewriter space-bar. When a notch 103 in the cam 96 comes opposite a shoulder on the bar 104, the latter moves under a vibrating bar 110, the lever frame 106 is depressed, and the clutch is disengaged. The clutch may be similarly operated by a second cam after the line has reached a given length independently of the typewriter space-bar. The machine is automatically stopped at the end of a paragraph or message by a bar 53, which is operated by a special perforation in the tape and is connected to the lever frame 106. In a modification of the apparatus, the selector pins 27 are carried by the selector plates 21, and the plates which are not displaced arrest the motion of the combs 36.

column12: Improvements in and relating to Wood-splitting Machinery.
column13: 24,552. Clerk, A. B., Hill, F. J., and Herbert, W. Nov. 10. Cutting - up, splitting, and slicing.-Figs. 1, 2, and 3 show a machine for splitting firewood and the like. The driving- shaft has a crank by which the blocks F are reciprocated in guides E, E. These blocks are flanged at G, and bolted together, and are preferably made in one with the knife-holders K, M. The holder K carries two splitting - knives L, L , placed at right-angles to one another, and the holder M carries a single knife N for splitting blocks which are too wide to enter the feedtrough P. The knives L pass through slots in the plate U, which is adjustable vertically by means of a screw W, to suit the depth of the blocks to be cut. The plate is carried by a slide V, which moves between guides on the framing. The blocks are placed in the trough by hand, and are fed by toothed rollers s, s' rotated intermittently by the means shown in Fig. 2. On the spindles of the rollers are grooved wheels a, a<1>, with which gear pawls c, c', carried by the levers b, b<1>. The levers b, b<1> are connected by a link, and are rocked by an adjustable pin in the crank-disc n. A pawl e prevents the backward movement of the rollers. The top roller is pressed downwards by a spring. When the block is being split it rests at one side against a metal-faced block of india-rubber; let into a recess in one side of the trough P. In one modification, the feed-rollers are driven by wormgear from a spindle, which is rotated by a friction pawl, as described above. In another the feeding is effected by serrated plates, reciprocating in slots in the plate U, and the bottom of the trough.

column13: A face and environment sensing portable device. In a preferred embodiment, the device is wrist-worn by a person, similarly to a wristwatch. The portable device includes one or more sensing elements, such as an image-capturing device, a microphone or other environmental sensor, and a processing system for processing data obtained from the sensing element(s). In addition, the portable device may include input/output elements for interfacing the portable device with a person and with external systems. The portable device reliably authenticates the identity of the person based on information obtained from the sensing element(s) and may also determine whether the user has been in continuous possession of the device. By using multi-modal identification, the invention may provide increased confidence, while maintaining a low cost. This verification may then be used, for example, to enable the person to conduct secure transactions.

column12: SYSTEM FOR PROCESSING RETAIL CLINIC CLAIMS
column13: A method for electronically determining patient medical treatment eligibility, coverage, copayment amount and insurer billing, by: (a) a patient requesting medical treatment at a retail clinic; (b) the patient presenting a health insurance card at the retail clinic; (c) the retail clinic transmitting patient health insurance card information to a centralized adjudication facility; (d) the retail clinic transmitting medical treatment information to the centralized adjudication facility; (e) the centralized adjudication facility determining patient medical treatment coverage, eligibility and copayment amount (f) transmitting the patient medical treatment coverage, eligibility and copayment amount from the centralized adjudication facility to the retail clinic; (g) the patient purchasing the medical treatment by paying the retail clinic the copayment amount, (h) transmitting a bill to the health care insurance provider; and (i) thereby informing the retail clinic clinician to sell the medical treatment to the patient. By simultaneously billing the patient and the insurer, the present invention provides a system that processes the sale of the medical treatment as a sales transaction.

column13: A variable geometry turbine comprises a turbine wheel (9) supported in a housing (1) for rotation about an axis. A nozzle ring (5) is moveably mounted within a cavity (19) provided within the housing for adjustment of the width of an annular inlet passageway (4) extending radially inwards towards the turbine wheel (9). An array of inlet guide vanes (8) extends between a radial face of the nozzle ring (5) and an opposing wall of the inlet (4) defining a radial vane passage. A first circumferential array of apertures (25) is provided through the radial face, each of which lies substantially within the vane passage. A second circumferential array of apertures (24) is also provided in said radial face, each of lies substantially upstream or downstream of the first array (25) of apertures. The inlet (4) and cavity (19) are in fluid communication via both the first and second sets of apertures (25, 24). ® KIPO & WIPO 2008

column13: A water purification system comprising a reverse osmosis unit (50) to separate feed water as product water and waste water, a reservoir (90) having bladder controlled expandable and contractible product water and control water chambers (94, 95, 96) and a control valve subsystem. The control valve subsystem includes a feed water shut-off valve (10) and a regulating valve (30). The shut-off valve (10) has a control chamber (20) subjected to product water pressure to control its open-closed condition, and is effective to close it at a predetermined upper limit of product water pressure. The regulating valve (30) includes two diaphragm areas (A1, A2) on a single moving element, two diaphragm operated valves (37, 38) (only one of which can be open at one time), and a relief valve (46). The regulating valve (30) is responsive to a demand for bladder control water to the reservoir (90) on diaphragm area (A1) to establish a first and higher level of control water flowing to the reservoir (90), and is also responsive to an excess of bladder control water flowing from the reservoir acting on diaphragm areas (A1) and (A2) to establish a second and lower level of control water back pressure in the reservoir (90).

column12: SYSTEM, COMPUTER PROGRAM PRODUCT AND METHOD FOR USING A CONVOLUTION NEURAL NETWORK TO AUTO-DETERMINE A FLOOR HEIGHT AND FLOOR HEIGHT ELEVATION OF A BUILDING
column13: A system, apparatus, computer program product, and method automatically, accurately, and reliably detect floor elevations of improvements (e.g., houses) on parcels of land without human inspection of the property. Fusing aspects of image processing, artificial intelligence, and information on adjacent grade points along the footprint of a specific property, the present computer-based system identifies a first floor height (FFH), and first floor elevation (FFE) of the improvement with respect to the terrain or surface of the parcel of land on which the improvement is located. In turn, by knowing the FFH of the improvement on the parcel, it is possible to improve on conventional methods for estimating flood risk to a property without requiring a personal inspection of the parcel by a human.

column12: THREE DIMENSIONAL CONTRIVER TOOL FOR MODELING WITH MULTI-TOUCH DEVICES
column13: A method, apparatus, article of manufacture, and computer readable storage medium provides the ability to perform a three-dimensional (3D) modeling operation. A modeling tool is activated in a 3D modeling application. A visual representation (having three separate regions) of a grid system tool is displayed on a digital modeling canvas of the 3D modeling application. The grid system controls whether a gesture is captured as a modeling operation or a navigation operation. A starting touch event (of the gesture) is received in/on one of the three separate regions. The region where the starting touch event is received determines the operation that is to be performed/selected. The operation may be a 3D geometry creation operation, a restroking operation, or a navigation operation.

ii) una puerta de salida del agua producto y iii) una puerta de salida del agua de desecho; una válvula de agua de alimentación, para controlar el flujo del agua de alimentación a la puerta de entrada de la unidad de filtración; una línea de desagüe, para transportar el agua de desecho desde la puerta del agua de desecho a un drenaje; un elemento de restricción en la línea de desagüe, adaptado para permitir el flujo del agua de desecho al drenaje, el cual es continuo cuando se abre la válvula del agua de alimentación, y para mantener una retropresión durante el flujo continuo; un depósito, que tiene un separador móvil, que divide el depósito en una cámara de agua producto y una cámara de agua de control, el depósito tiene una puerta del agua producto que comunica con la cámara del agua producto, y una puerta del agua de control que comunica con la cámara de agua de control; una conexión de salida para la descarga de uso final del agua producto; y elementos que suministran la comunicación de fluido entre la puerta de salida del agua producto de la unidad de filtración y la puerta del agua producto del depósito y la conexión de salida, de modo que el agua producto pueda ser suministrada al depósito y a la conexión de salida, la mejora que comprende: un elemento regulador conectado a i) la puerta de salida del agua de deecho de la unidad de filtración, ii) la puerta de agua de control del depósito y iii) la línea de desagüe, el elemento regulador comprende una primera válvula, eficaz cuando se abre para suministrar el agua de desperdicio desde la puerta de salida del agua de desecho de la unidad de filtración como agua de control a la puerta de agua de control del depósito, para empujar el separador móvil del depósito hacia la cámara de agua producto para facilitar la remoción del agua producto desde la cámara de agua producto a la conexión de salida, y el elemento regulador comprende una segunda válvula y un elemento que mantiene la retropresión, esta segunda válvula es eficaz cuando se abre para desaguar el agua de control desde la puerta del agua de control del depósito, a través del elemento que mantiene la retropresión a la línea de desagüe y así realizar una reducción en la presión del agua de control en la cámara del agua de control; column13: A method of improving the stability and broadening the range of pH stability of an aqueous solution of from about 0.001 % to 5 % by weight of a water soluble organosilane containing hydrolyzable groups such as methyltrimethoxysilane, 3-(trimethoxysilyl)propyldimethyloctadecyl ammonium chloride and 3-(trimethoxysilyl)-propylmethyldi(decyl) ammonium chloride by the use of 0.05 % to 10 % by weight of a water soluble organic quaternary ammonium compound having at least one nitrogen-bonded hydrocarbon group of at least 8 carbon atoms and being free of silicon atoms, such as benzalkonium chloride, along with from about 0.5 % to 30 % by weight of at least one surfactant selected from the group consisting of nonionic, amphoteric sarcosine anionic, and cationic surfactants other than the water soluble quaternary ammonium compounds. The pH of the solution can be adjusted to from about 1 to about 13.5 with a suitable acid or base. The resulting stable aqueous solutions are useful for depositing the water soluble organosilane on a variety of substrates to, among other things, serve as coupling agents, waterproofing agents and to render substrates antimicrobial and algicidal depending upon the nature of the organosilane.

column13: A modeling tool is activated in a 3D modeling application executing on a multi-touch device. A visual representation of a grid system tool is displayed in an active modeling plane and has three separate regions that determine the type of operation to be performed. An existing 3D form is displayed on the tool. A starting touch event of a gesture is received over the existing 3D form within one of the regions. As the gesture is received in the computer, the 3D form may be dynamically extended by adding 3D geometry to the 3D form (thereby adding faces to the 3D form). Alternatively, the 3D form may be scaled (i.e., if the starting touch event occurs over a visual scale grip. Alternatively, if the gesture consists of two taps, a bridge may be created joining the two tapped locations.

column13: Un système de purification d'eau comprend une unité d'osmose inverse (5) servant à séparer l'eau d'alimentation en eau de consommation et en eau perdue, un réservoir (90) comportant des chambres d'eau de consommation et d'eau de commande expansibles et contractiles et commandées par vessie (94, 95, 96) et un sous-système à soupape de commande. Le système à soupape de commande comprend une soupape d'arrêt (10) pour l'eau d'alimentation et une soupape de régulation (30). La soupape d'arrêt (10) comporte une chambre de commande (20) soumise à la pression de l'eau de consommation servant à commander l'ouverture et la fermeture de la soupape et servant à fermer la soupape à une limite supérieure prédéterminée de pression de l'eau de consommation. La soupape de régulation (30) comprend deux zones à diaphragme (A1, A2) placées sur un seul élément mobile, deux soupapes actionnées par diaphragme (37, 38) (dont une seulement peut être ouverte à la fois) et une soupape de décharge (46). La soupape de régulation (30) réagit à une demande d'eau de commande de vessie pour le réservoir (90) sur la zone de diaphragme (A1), de façon à établir un premier niveau supérieur d'eau de commande s'écoulant vers le réservoir (90), et réagit également à un excès d'eau de commande de vessie s'écoulant depuis le réservoir et agissant sur les zones à diaphragme (A1 et A2), de façon à établir un second niveau inférieur de pression de rotation pour de l'eau de commande dans le réservoir (90).

column13: A variable geometry turbine comprises a turbine wheel (9) supported in a housing (1) for rotation about an axis. A nozzle ring (5) is moveably mounted within a cavity (19) provided within the housing for adjustment of the width of an annular inlet passageway (4) extending radially inwards towards the turbine wheel (9). An array of inlet guide vanes (8) extends between a radial face of the nozzle ring (5) and an opposing wall of the inlet (4) defining a radial vane passage. A first circumferential array of apertures (25) is provided through the radial face, each of which lies substantially within the vane passage. A second circumferential array of apertures (24) is also provided in said radial face, each of lies substantially upstream or downstream of the first array (25) of apertures. The inlet (4) and cavity (19) are in fluid communication via both the first and second sets of apertures (25, 24).

column13: Systems, devices, non-transitory computer storage mediums, and methods are described herein for pharmaceutical benefits management including routing pharmaceutical claims over a computer network. The system includes a computer network and a client device communicatively coupled to the computer network. The client device is configured to receive order information representative of a prescription drug prescribed for a consumer. The system includes a communications switch configured to derive a processor control number associated with the order information and route the order information based on the processor control number. The system includes a pharmaceutical benefits manager configured to authorize the prescription drug with the reimbursement based on the processor control number and configured to transmit the authorization with the reimbursement to the client device.

column13: A face and environment sensing portable device. In a preferred embodiment, the device is wrist-worn by a person, similarly to a wristwatch. The portable device includes one or more sensing elements, such as an image-capturing device, a microphone or other environmental sensor, and a processing system for processing data obtained from the sensing element(s). In addition, the portable device may include input/output elements for interfacing the portable device with a person and with external systems. The portable device reliably authenticates the identity of the person based on information obtained from the sensing element(s) and may also determine whether the user has been in continuous possession of the device. By using multi-modal identification, the invention may provide increased confidence, while maintaining a low cost. This verification may then be used, for example, to enable the person to conduct secure transactions. The verification may also be used to tailor or customize applications and services to the user's personal preferences. The invention avoids drawbacks of conventional authentication techniques, such as inaccuracies in manual photographic identification techniques and the proliferation of excessive numbers of passwords. In another aspect, the invention overcomes drawbacks in the abilities of low-cost image sensors by applying superresolution techniques to combine multiple lower quality images into an image with improved quality. Super-resolution processing can be performed in the portable device itself or by an external infrastructure.

column12: Use of a convolutional neural network to auto-determine a floor height and floor height elevation of a building
column13: A system, apparatus, computer program product, and method use a convolutional neural network to auto-determine a first floor height (FFH) and a FFH elevation (FFE) of a building. The FFH, and FFE of the building are determined with respect to the terrain or surface of the parcel of land on which the building is located. In turn, by knowing the FFH and/or FFE of the building on the parcel, it is possible to use that information while performing a flood risk assessment to a property without requiring a personal inspection of the parcel by a human.

By simultaneously billing the patient and the insurer, the present invention provides a system that processes the sale of the medical treatment as a sales transaction.

column13: "A water purification system has a reverse osmosis filtration unit which receives feed water from a feed water valve and separates it into product water and waste water. A reservoir has a movable separator dividing it into a product water chamber for receiving the product water and a control water chamber. The product water is delivered to an outlet connection from the product water chamber or directly from the filtration unit. A regulator is connected to the waste water outlet port of the filtration unit, the control water port of the reservoir, and a drain line. The regulator has a first valve for providing waste water from the filtration unit to the control water port of the reservoir for urging the separator toward the product water chamber. The regulator has a second valve that can rapidly drain water from the control water chamber of the reservoir and rapidly reduce pressure in the control water chamber, thus facilitating the refilling of the product water chamber. A relief valve downstream of the second valve maintains a low pressure in the system to avoid undesirable cycling of the system between high pressure and low pressure."

Stretchers, garment; presses; trousers; trouser stretchers ; linen presses.-A combined stretcher and presser for linen, trousers, and other garments, consists of a lower board, Fig. 1, and an upper board, Fig. 2. The lower one is made in two parts a, a<1>, hinged together so as to fold upwards. The upper one is made in parts a<2>, a<3>, a<4>, a<5>, connected crosswise by bars c<3>, c<4>, c<5>, c<6>, to form two multiple parts hinged together at b<2>. These fold downwards. Stiff ears stand up from the opposite edges of the bottom board and form supports for cam-levers d<1>, d<2>, the ends of which are connected by cross-rods f. The cam-levers enable pressure to be applied to bent metal strips h, h<1>, which serve to hold the garment. The trousers or other garments are placed on the lower board, which is folded while the ends of the trousers are clamped between the holders h, h<1>. The upper board, which is recessed at the ends between horns j to allow for the holders, is then placed over the trousers which are stretched by straightening out the boards. Pressure is applied to the middle of the boards through a bar k pivoted at its centre to a cross-bar c<5> on the upper board and adapted to swing into coincidence with the cross-bar. Its ends are then engaged by camlevers mounted similarly to those at the ends. The cam-levers may be replaced by screws.

column12: METHOD FOR PROVIDING CONSUMER CHOICE AND EQUALIZING PHARMACY PROVIDER AVAILABILITY IN PRESCRIPTION MEDICATION DISPENSING PLANS
column13: A method is disclosed whereby consumers enrolled in a prescription benefit plan can obtain prescription medication fulfillment at any participating pharmacy of their choice, regardless of whether the fulfillment is by a retail pharmacy or a mail order pharmacy, and whether the quantity of medication prescribed is for administration over a short period (acute care) or a prolonged period (maintenance). The plan of this invention operates by having the plan manager substantially equalize the financial effects of the discounts and services fees allowed to participating pharmacies such that both retail and mail order pharmacies are compensated in a manner which encourages them to accept all consumers and fill all prescriptions. Compensation is preferably adjusted periodically by the manager to retain pharmacy incentives. Consumers obtain choice of pharmacies, plan payers have pleased employees and members and pharmacies obtain income from the entire spectrum of consumers.

column13: A face and environment sensing portable device. In a preferred embodiment, the device is wrist-worn by a person, similarly to a wristwatch. The portable device includes one or more sensing elements, such as an image-capturing device, a microphone or other environmental sensor, and a processing system for processing data obtained from the sensing element(s). In addition, the portable device may include input/output elements for interfacing the portable device with a person and with external systems. The portable device reliably authenticates the identity of the person based on information obtained from the sensing element(s) and may also determine whether the user has been in continuous possession of the device. By using multi-modal identification, the invention may provide increased confidence, while maintaining a low cost. This verification may then be used, for example, to enable the person to conduct secure transactions. The verification may also be used to tailor or customize applications and services to the user's personal preferences. The invention avoids drawbacks of conventional authentication techniques, such as inaccuracies in manual photographic identification techniques and the proliferation of excessive numbers of passwords. In another aspect, the invention overcomes drawbacks in the abilities of low-cost image sensors by applying superresolution techniques to combine multiple lower quality images into an image with improved quality. Super-resolution processing can be performed in the portable device itself or by an external infrastructure.

column12: Improvements in vibrating spreader feeders for granular or particulate materials
column13: 842,560. Jigging conveyers; trimming materials. SIMON Ltd., H. Feb. 3, 1959 [Feb. 10, 1958; Aug. 22, 1958], Nos. 4226/58 and 27026/58. Classes 78 (1) and 78 (4). A vibrating spreader feeder comprises a relatively long narrow tapered tray 1 which has a discharge edge 8 cut on a bias and a series of longitudinal vertical guides 9 arranged parallel to the direction of reciprocatory motion to cause the material to be discharged in a substantially uniform curtain. The upper edges of the guides are inclined downwards towards the edge 8. The guides may be replaced by a substantially vertical weir-plate mounted along the edge 8. This plate tapers downwardly from the feed end of the tray and has means for adjusting the height and slope of its top edge. It may also consist of a series of thin plates 24, Fig. 5, adjustably clamped together by a bar 23 so that their upper edges approximate to a shallow arc. The tray is supported by pivoted arms 2 and is reciprocated by a rotary cam 4 which engages a follower 6 on the rear end of the tray. A counterbalanced shoot 12 is mounted pivotally in upward extensions 10 of the tray and is disposed below a fixed hopper 17 in such a way that materials can escape only through the gap 18 between its mouth and the surface of the shoot. The shoot is counterbalanced by an adjustable spring 15 in conjunction with a dashpot 16. An extension 20 of the shoot 12 operates a mechanical linkage, electrical switch-gear, or pneumatic or hydraulic valve gear 19 immediately before the lower and upper limits of travel of the shoot to start, stop or control the speed of either the feeder or processing machinery associated therewith.

column12: GESTURES AND TOOLS FOR CREATING AND EDITING SOLID MODELS
column13: A modeling tool is activated in a 3D modeling application executing on a multi-touch device. A visual representation of a grid system tool is displayed in an active modeling plane and has three separate regions that determine the type of operation to be performed. An existing 3D form is displayed on the tool. A starting touch event of a gesture is received over the existing 3D form within one of the regions. As the gesture is received in the computer, the 3D form may be dynamically extended by adding 3D geometry to the 3D form (thereby adding faces to the 3D form). Alternatively, the 3D form may be scaled (i.e., if the starting touch event occurs over a visual scale grip. Alternatively, if the gesture consists of two taps, a bridge may be created joining the two tapped locations.

column12: Selection of ad units of a compound advertisement for display
column13: In an embodiment, a digital data specification of a compound advertisement comprising a plurality of ad units is received at an advertisement delivery server computer, where the digital data specification of the compound advertisement specifies one or more sequential dependencies between one or more ad units of the plurality of ad units and a bid value for each ad unit of the plurality of ad units. Based at least in part on a particular sequential dependency of the first ad unit upon a second ad unit of the same compound advertisement and a bid value associated with the first ad unit, a first ad unit of the compound advertisement is selected for display at a separate user computing device using the advertisement delivery server computer. column13: - 0a WATER PURIFICATION SYSTEM A water purification system comprising a reverse osmosis unit (50) to separate feed water as product water and waste water, a reservoir (90) having bladder controlled expandable and contractible product water and control water chambers (94, 95, 96) and a control valve subsystem. The control valve subsystem includes a feed water shut-off valve (10) and a regulating valve (30). The shut-off valve (10) has a control chamber (20) subjected to product water pressure to control its open-closed condition, and is effective to close it at a predetermined upper limit of product water pressure. The regulating valve (30) includes two diaphragm areas (A1, A2) on a single moving element, two diaphragm operated valves (37, 38) (only one of which can be open at one time), and a relief valve (46). The regulating valve (30) is responsive to a demand for bladder control water to the reservoir (90) on diaphragm area (A1) to establish a first and higher level of control water flowing to the reservoir (90), and is also responsive to an excess of bladder control water flowing from the reservoir acting on diaphragm areas (A1) and (A2) to establish a second and lower level of control water back pressure in the reservoir (90). The regulating valve (30) thus automatically senses whether the system is requiring control water to be fed into the control water chamber (96) to raise its pressure level; or is requiring control water to be relieved from the control water chamber (96) to reduce its pressure level. The higher pressure of control water is desired as the motive pressure for delivery of product water at the faucet or ice maker (100); the -0b-lower back pressure of control water, during production and filling, enhances flow through the filtration unit (50).

column13: A system, apparatus, computer program product, and method use a convolutional neural network to auto-determine a first floor height (FFH) and a FFH elevation (FFE) of a building. The FFH, and FFE of the building are determined with respect to the terrain or surface of the parcel of land on which the building is located. column13: A method of improving the stability and broadening the range of pH stability of an aqueous solution of from about 0.001 % to 5 % by weight of a water soluble organosilane containing hydrolyzable groups such as methyltrimethoxysilane, 3-(trimethoxysilyl)propyldimethyloctadecyl ammonium chloride and 3-(trimethoxysilyl)-propylmethyldi(decyl) ammonium chloride by the use of 0.05 % to 10 % by weight of a water soluble organic quaternary ammonium compound having at least one nitrogen-bonded hydrocarbon group of at least 8 carbon atoms and being free of silicon atoms, such as benzalkonium chloride, along with from about 0.5 % to 30 % by weight of at least one surfactant selected from the group consisting of nonionic, amphoteric sarcosine anionic, and cationic surfactants other than the water soluble quaternary ammonium compounds. The pH of the solution can be adjusted to from about 1 to about 13.5 with a suitable acid or base. The resulting stable aqueous solutions are useful for depositing the water soluble organosilane on a variety of substrates to, among other things, serve as coupling agents, waterproofing agents and to render substrates antimicrobial and algicidal depending upon the nature of the organosilane.

column13: A face and environment sensing portable device. In a preferred embodiment, the device is wrist-worn by a person, similarly to a wristwatch. The portable device includes one or more sensing elements, such as an image-capturing device, a microphone or other environmental sensor, and a processing system for processing data obtained from the sensing element(s). In addition, the portable device may include input/output elements for interfacing the portable device with a person and with external systems. The portable device reliably authenticates the identity of the person based on information obtained from the sensing element(s) and may also determine whether the user has been in continuous possession of the device. By using multi-modal identification, the invention may provide increased confidence, while maintaining a low cost. This verification may then be used, for example, to enable the person to conduct secure transactions. The verification may also be used to tailor or customize applications and services to the user's personal preferences. The invention avoids drawbacks of conventional authentication techniques, such as inaccuracies in manual photographic identification techniques and the proliferation of excessive numbers of passwords. In another aspect, the invention overcomes drawbacks in the abilities of low-cost image sensors by applying superresolution techniques to combine multiple lower quality images into an image with improved quality. Super-resolution processing can be performed in the portable device itself or by an external infrastructure.

column12: Gestures and tools for creating and editing solid models
column13: A modeling tool is activated in a 3D modeling application executing on a multi-touch device. A visual representation of a grid system tool is displayed in an active modeling plane and has three separate regions that determine the type of operation to be performed. An existing 3D form is displayed on the tool. A starting touch event of a gesture is received over the existing 3D form within one of the regions. As the gesture is received in the computer, the 3D form may be dynamically extended by adding 3D geometry to the 3D form (thereby adding faces to the 3D form). Alternatively, the 3D form may be scaled (i.e., if the starting touch event occurs over a visual scale grip. Alternatively, if the gesture consists of two taps, a bridge may be created joining the two tapped locations.

column12: Method for determining position within the measuring volume of a coordinate measuring machine and the like and system therefor.
column13: Axis correction or machine characteristic data is stored (108) in memory (110) within a control or measurement processor (36) of a CMM (10) (FIGURE 8). The axis correction data includes error data representing 21 different geometry errors (FIGURES 4A through 4C) of the CMM. As position information is required, the measurement processor captures the actual position signal from each machine axis sensor and uses this position signal to locate (112) a set of the axis correction data which describes the machine characteristics at that position. The measurement processor then mathematically combines (114) (FIGURE 9) the position signal with the subset of axis correction data to obtain a corrected position signal having a corrected set of coordinate values which describe the probe position in a true Cartesian coordinate system.

column13: Novel tools and techniques for providing a subscriber with converged voice services, in which calls to one of the subscriber's telephone numbers is routed to some or all of the subscriber's telephone numbers (e.g., sequentially or simultaneously, depending on system configuration and/or subscriber preference). Some implementations employ a VoIP switch to handle call distribution among the subscriber's various phone lines, even if some (or all) of the subscribers telephone lines are not VoIP lines. In such implementations, upon receiving an incoming call directed to one of the subscriber's lines, a service switching point will route the call to a VoIP switch. Instructed by an application server, the VoIP switch will set up call legs (e.g., via the PSTN) to one or more of the subscribers' telephone numbers. Optionally, when one of the call legs is answered, the application server will instruct the VoIP switch to disconnect the other call legs.

column12: Process for making fluid coke agglomerates
column13: <PICT:0988033/C4-C5/1> A method of making pellets from coke particles derived from a fluidized bed oil coking process, e.g. as described in Specification 752,400, comprises mixing a carbonaceous binder with the coke particles in an amount between 5% and 35% by weight of the mix at a temperature at least 5 DEG F. above the softening point of the binder, cooling, granulating the cooled lumps to a size less than 2 inches and preferably 1/2 inch, and passing the resultant pieces through a die to form the pellets. Binders used are petroleum base pitch, asphalt binder or coal tar pitch binder, and should have a softening point between 140 DEG and 250 DEG F. Heated binder is atomized at 32 with steam at 250 DEG to 325 DEG F. and led to a mixer 10 for mixing with one or more coke streams at 16, 24. Alternatively, the binder may be sprayed into the mixer 10 or added in lump form, or the coke may be fluidized and the binder sprayed therein. Mixing is continued for up to 1 hour, e.g. 20 to 30 minutes, the mixture, preferably after quenching at 44, being delivered to a conveyer 42 for cooling to 70 DEG to 80 DEG F., i.e. to between 30 DEG and 175 DEG F. below the softening point of the binder, and thence to a granulator 48, feeder 54, and pellet mill 56, the die of which has holes 0.5 to 3 inches in length and 0.25 to 1 inch in diameter. The die may be heated or cooled. The pellets are cooled, and may be baked at 1200 DEG to 2000 DEG F., e.g. after mixing with coke from a fluidized bed oil coking process.

column12: MOBILE ION GETTERER FOR METAL CONDUCTORS
column13: A mobile ion getterer is added to metalization layers on an integrated circuit or discrete device to reduce mobile ion contamination therein. Preferably, chromium is used as the mobile ion getterer and is added to an aluminum target used as the metal source for sputtering the chromium and aluminum onto the integrated circuit or discrete device. This technique removes the need for ultra-high purity aluminum conductors or gettering material (P-glass) in contact with the metal conductors. This technique may be used with virtually all metalization apparatus and processes used for depositing metal onto semiconductor devices.

column12: Improvements in and relating to the determination and control of compositions in chemical processes by titration
column13: <PICT:0855708/III/1> <PICT:0855708/III/2> An automatic titration apparatus comprises (1) a vessel V (Fig. 1) with electrical level detector 8, electrical draining valve 2, stirrer (not shown) and end-point detector E1 E2; (2) at least one burette B with level detector 12 and filling and emptying valves 6, 7, also fitted with level-finder b; (3) one or more pipettes A, C, for reagents and diluents, these also having level detectors 9, 10, 11, filling valves 1, 3, and emptying valves 4, 5; (4) an electrical circuit associated with the end-point detector E1 E2 (Fig. 5) to give a signal which changes as the end-point is approached, this signal being passed through an anticipation circuit and a trigger circuit to control the outlet valve of the burette so that the reagent is added in discrete amounts with increasingly longer intervals; and (5) a sequencing switch (Fig. 6, not shown) controlled by the level detectors of the burette(s), pipette(s) and titration vessel and by the end-point detector, to control the various electromagnetic valves so that the operations of filling, titrating, measuring and emptying are performed in the correct order. The end-point detector is preferably a pH meter but may instead be based on change of colour, conductivity or redox potential. The pipettes A, C, are shown as one being of the overflow type and the other having an electrical level detector but these two types are interchangeable. The device b is preferably a photo-cell and lamp for detecting the liquid meniscus, but other kinds of electrical and mechanical level-gauges are mentioned as suitable. Stirring of the titration vessel may be effected by a mechanical stirrer or by blowing an inert gas through the liquid. The sample can be introduced manually or automatically and the apparatus can be arranged to cut off after the end-point is reached or to re-set itself to receive another sample. The sequence of operations is as follows (referring to Fig. 1):-(1) all valves are shut except 1, vessel V is full from the previous titration, and the sample is flowing through A; (2) valve 1 closes, b moves towards its rest position (continuing through subsequent operations (3) to (6) if necessary), valve 2 opens and vessel empties; (3) valve 2 shuts and 3 opens, filling C with diluent; (4) valve 3 shuts and 4 opens, passing diluent into V; (5) valve 4 shuts and 5 opens, delivering sample into V; (6) valve 5 shuts and 6 opens to fill burette; (7) valve 6 shuts and 7 opens, and titration commences; when about 90% of the correct amount has been delivered the circuit mentioned above comes into play and interrupts the flow from the burette for increasingly long intervals (up to 30 sec. in the end); (8) valve 7 has now closed and the device b records the level in the burette. The device b which detects the level of liquid in the burette is driven by a motor which also operates an indicator or recorder to show the amount of titrant added.

column12: USER VALIDATION SYSTEM UTILIZING SYMBOLIC OR PICTOGRAPHIC REPRESENTATIONS OF VALIDATION CODES
column13: Disclosed herein is a device and method for validating users, such as for entry into a given area. The method includes transmitting a plurality of access control tokens from an access control system to a portable device, and detecting proximity a user portable device associated with one of the plurality of access control tokens to the portable device. A symbolic representation of the access control token associated with the user portable device is generated by and displayed on the portable device. Selection of the displayed symbolic representation is accepted at the portable device. The access control system is notified of selection of the displayed symbolic representation, thereby indicating identification of a user associated with the access control token symbolically represented by the symbolic representation. The venue symbolic representation includes at least one pictograph.

column13: A process for the production of ethyl acrylate comprises continuously feeding a mixture containing acrylic acid and at least one mole of ethanol per mole of acrylic acid into a reactor which is maintained at an elevated temperature and which contains an acid catalyst, continuously distilling overhead a fraction containing ethyl acrylate and substantially all the water produced in the esterification or introduced with the feed, and controlling the concentration of polymeric material by continuous removal of a liquid stream containing polymeric material from the reaction mixture. The distillation may be effected in the presence of an entrainer such as ethyl acetate or ethyl acrylate and the former may be produced in situ by the use of a feed to the reactor comprising a mixture of acrylic and acetic acids. Ethyl acrylate and entrainer maybe recovered from the overhead fraction by, for example, azeotropic distillation or extractive distillation, the entrainer being preferably returned to the reactor. The acid catalyst is preferably sulphuric acid. The liquid stream continuously removed from the reactor may be treated to separate volatile material from polymeric material, the volatile material preferably being returned to the reactor. Examples are given.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR DIVERTING A GUIDED MISSILE
column13: The disclosed system, device, and method for diverting a guided missile generally includes a ground-based sensor array generating tracking data of a guided missile tracking a target. A control node in communication with the ground-based sensor array generates targeting data from the tracking data. A phased array directed-energy unit in communication with the control node radiates the guided missile with variable beam width microwave radiation based on the targeting data received from the control node, where the microwave radiation disrupts an electronic component of the guided missile such that the guided missile discontinues tracking the target.

column13: 1,137,061. Electro-chemical deburring of metal workpieces. ASSOCIATED ENG. Ltd. Dec.10, 1965 [Dec. 14, 1964], No.50852/64. Heading C7B. In a method of deburring metal workpieces by electro-chemical machining in which a deburring tool is arranged in close proximity to the region or regions to be deburred such that the tool and workpiece are maintained in fixed positions during the deburring operation, the tool and the workpiece being connected into an electrical circuit such that the workpiece forms an anode and the tool forms a cathode, electrolyte being present therebetween, the tool employed is shaped so as to conform to the shape of the region or. regions to be deburred. The tool may be formed using as pattern a workpiece which has been deburred, either by casting metal about the workpiece and removing therefrom said casting which thus conforms to the workpiece, or by means of a reverse electrochemical machining process in which the workpiece forms the cathode and a tool blank forms the anode. The tool may be partially coated with insulating material to restrict electrolytic action to the required regions, Fig. 3 (not shown). In the apparatus shown for carrying out the method of the invention a gear-wheel 18 which forms the workpiece to be deburred is mounted on a base 19 and within an enclosure 23, the deburring tool 21 being mounted above said workpiece, and electrolyte is supplied to the enclosure via pipe 25 to pass through the gap 22 between the tool 21 and workpiece 18 to discharge via outlet 27. A desired pressure may be maintained within the enclosure by means of pressure valve 28. After the deburring operation has taken place compressed air may be admitted to the enclosure via inlet 30 to blow out electrolyte from the enclosure and partially dry the workpiece.

column13: Novel tools and techniques for providing a subscriber with converged voice services, in which calls to one of the subscriber's telephone numbers is routed to some or all of the subscriber's telephone numbers (e.g., sequentially or simultaneously, depending on system configuration and/or subscriber preference). Some implementations employ a VoIP switch to handle call distribution among the subscriber's various phone lines, even if some (or all) of the subscribers telephone lines are not VoIP lines. In such implementations, upon receiving an incoming call directed to one of the subscriber's lines, a service switching point will route the call to a VoIP switch. Instructed by an application server, the VoIP switch will set up call legs (e.g., via the PSTN) to one or more of the subscribers' telephone numbers. Optionally, when one of the call legs is answered, the application server will instruct the VoIP switch to disconnect the other call legs.

column13: A digital hearing aid is provided that includes front and rear microphone s, a sound processor, and a speaker. Embodiments of the digital hearing aid include an occlusion subsystem, and a directional processor and headroom expander. T he front microphone receives a front microphone acoustical signal and generates a front microphone analog signal. The rear microphone receives a rear micropho ne acoustical signal and generates a rear microphone analog signal. The front a nd rear microphone analog signals are converted into the digital domain, and at least the front microphone signal is coupled to the sound processor. The sound processor selectively modifies the signal characteristics and generates a processed signal. The processed signal is coupled to the speaker which converts the signal to an acoustical hearing aid output signal that is directed into the ear can al of the digital hearing aid user. The occlusion sub-system compensates for the amplification of the digital hearing aid user's own voice within the ear canal. The directional processor and headroom expander optimizes the gain applied to th e acoustical signals received by the digital hearing aid and combine the amplified signals into a directionally-sensitive response.

column12: Method for calibrating a coordinate measuring machine and the like and system therefor
column13: Method (FIGS. 4A through 4C) and system (FIG. 3) are disclosed for automatically calibrating a coordinate measuring machine (CMM) (10). The system guides an operator through instrument set-up and data collection procedures. The system automatically converts the collected data into error compensation or axis correction data which represents 21 different geometry errors (i.e. pitch, yaw, roll etc.) of the CMM (10). The error compensation data is then transferred to a CMM measurement processor (36) for subsequent use by the CMM (10) during operation thereof to thereby compensate the CMM (10) for its entire measuring volume (102).

column13: A kilowatt-scale high-frequency electrical power conversion system adapted for variable output power delivery is described, in which switching frequency of switchable power delivery circuitry is dynamically modulated in transition of the system to a low power regime that is substantially below maximum power output, in order to at least partially attenuate thermal overload from heat generation of switching components in such transitions. column13: METHOD FOR DETECTING POSITION WITHIN THE MEASURING VOLUME OF A COORDINATE MEASURING MACHINE AND THE LIKE AND SYSTEM THEREFOR Axis correction or machine characteristic data is stored (108) in memory (110) within a control or measurement processor (36) of a CMM (10) (FIGURE 8). The axis correction data includes error data representing 21 different geometry errors (FIGURES 4A through 4C) of the CMM. As position information is required, the measurement processor captures the actual position signal from each machine axis sensor and uses this position signal to locate (112) a set of the axis correction data which describes the machine characteristics at that position. The measurement processor then mathematically combines (114) (FIGURE 9) the position signal with the subset of axis correction data to obtain a corrected position signal having a corrected set of coordinate values which describe the probe position in a true Cartesian coordinate system.

column13: A reversible reservoir for cigarettes or filters includes relatively small and relatively large capacity sections arranged in series with means for driving these sections at different rates. The reservoir may be in the form of an elongated helix with an endless conveyor (2) passing around spaced columns of wheels (8, 10, 12, 14, 16), one of the lowermost wheels (8) being bodily movable so as to be capable of imposing an additional velocity on the section of conveyor adjacent the reservoir inlet (7). The movable wheel is carried on a beam (36) which also carries a pulley (26) for the conveyor return run. Tensioning means for the conveyor is provided by arranging for the position of the pulley (26) to be adjustable relative to the beam (36). <IMAGE>

column12: Improvements in methods and apparatus for electrochemical machining
column13: <PICT:1093932/C6-C7/1> In electro-chemically machining a metal or metallic workpiece, the machining tool is effectively moved towards the workpiece by causing relative movement between the tool and the workpiece in a series of discrete steps whilst an electric current is continuously passed between the tool and workpiece during the series of discrete step movements. As shown, a tool 3 is advanced towards a workpiece 1 by a stepping motor 5 which is driven in a series of discrete steps by a series of energizing pulses from a pulse generator 7, e.g. having an electronically stabilized frequency. A pulse counter 8 indicates the position of the tool, e.g. each pulse may give rise to a tool movement of 0.0001 inch. The rate and amount of tool advance may be controlled by means of a predetermined programme, e.g. set up on a punched card or tape or on magnetic tape.

column12: Method for calibrating a coordinate measuring machine and the like.
column13: Method (FIGURES 4A through 4C) and system (FIGURE 3) are disclosed for automatically calibrating a coordinate measuring machine (CMM) (10). The system guides an operator through instrument set-up and data collection procedures. The system automatically con­verts the collected data into error compensation or axis correction data which represents 21 different geometry errors (i.e. pitch, yaw, roll etc.) of the CMM (10). The error compensation data is then trans­ferred to a CMM measurement processor (36) for subse­quent use by the CMM (10) during operation thereof to thereby compensate the CMM (10) for its entire measuring volume (102).

column13: Novel tools and techniques for providing a subscriber with converged voice services, in which calls to one of the subscriber's telephone numbers is routed to some or all of the subscriber's telephone numbers (e.g., sequentially or simultaneously, depending on system configuration and/or subscriber preference). Some implementations employ a VoIP switch to handle call distribution among the subscriber's various phone lines, even if some (or all) of the subscribers telephone lines are not VoIP lines. In such implementations, upon receiving an incoming call directed to one of the subscriber's lines, a service switching point will route the call to a VoIP switch. Instructed by an application server, the VoIP switch will set up call legs (e.g., via the PSTN) to one or more of the subscribers' telephone numbers. Optionally, when one of the call legs is answered, the application server will instruct the VoIP switch to disconnect the other call legs.

column12: SYSTEM AND METHOD FOR DIVERTING A GUIDED MISSILE
column13: The disclosed system, device, and method for diverting a guided missile generally includes a ground-based sensor array generating tracking data of a guided missile tracking a target. A control node in communication with the ground-based sensor array generates targeting data from the tracking data. A phased array directed- energy unit in communication with the control node radiates the guided missile with variable beam width microwave radiation based on the targeting data received from the control node, where the microwave radiation disrupts an electronic component of the guided missile such that the guided missile discontinues tracking the target.

column12: Improvements in arrangements for feeding sheets or the like
column13: 719,954. Feeding sheets. BLOCK & ANDERSON, Ltd., and HALL TELEPHONE ACCESSORIES, Ltd. March 24, 1953 [March 31, 1952], No. 8159/52. Class 100 (1). Pile tables; ; sheet-separators.- In a sheet-separating apparatus the pile table for the sheets is pivotally mounted at or near the end remote from that from which the sheets are delivered, and is urged upwardly at the free end by spring means controlled by an escapement which is itself controlled by a detector engaging the .top sheet of the pile, whereby the top of the pile is kept at a desired level. As applied to a duplicating-machine, the pile table 5 is pivoted about a fixed axis 3, and is urged upwardly at the back or delivery end by a roller 15 carried on one end 14 of a bell-crank lever secured to a shaft 16, the other end 17 of the lever being attached to a tension spring 18. A pile of sheets is placed on the table 5 between adjustable side plates 6 and the table depressed against the action of the spring 18 to bring the top of the pile to the level of a plate 10 which is secured to the machine frame. The shaft 16 is coupled to a shaft 28 through a number of gear-wheels and a one-way clutch, so that as the table 5 is moved, an escapement wheel 29 on the shaft 28 is rotated: the clutch allows free depression of the table 5. The rotation of the wheel 29 is controlled by a rocker 30 to which is attached a pendulum arm 31 carrying a weight 32. When the pendulum 31, 32 is free to swing, its natural frequency determines the rate of movement of the escapement wheel 29. The upward movement of the table 5 is arrested, when the top of the sheet pile is at the correct level, by the free end of a lever 34 embracing a pin 33 secured to the rocker 30. The lever 34 is pivoted at 35 and attached to a link 36 which is guided for vertical movement by a detector responsive to the position of the top sheet of the pile. As shown, this detector comprises a friction or combing roller 11 which feeds the sheets from the pile, the roller being carried by an arm 12 pivoted at 13 and driven by known means. An arm 40 secured to the arm 12 is adapted to engage a pin 39 on the link 36 so that if the roller 11 drops below a certain level the link is lifted to release the rocker 30 and allow the spring 18 to raise the table 5. A latch 41 on the arm 40 can engage in a notch 43 in a plate 42 to enable the roller 11 to be retained in a raised position during loading of the table 5. The lower part 10<SP>1</SP> of the fixed plate 10 slopes away from the table 5 and acts to register the sheet pile by displacing it rearwardly as the table rises. An adjustable trip, to prevent upward movement of the table just before the pile of sheets is exhausted and to operate an electric trip in the drive of the machine if the machine is driven electrically, comprises an arm secured to the shaft 16 adapted to operate a link which stops the rotation of the roller 11 and the machine when the arm has been rotated through a predetermined arc by the shaft 16.

column13: A method and apparatus for filtering pulp fibers from a pulp slurry, using a combination of vacuum, hydrodynamic and hydrostatic forces in order to achieve a more effective deposition of pulp fibers onto the filter surface and enhanced flow of filtrate through the cylinder. The apparatus is in the form of an improved vacuum filtration system, in which the filtrate outlet tube is disposed along the axis of rotation of the rotary cylinder and the filtrate inlet and outlet ports of each filtrate conduct are radially offset from one another in the direction of intended rotation of the cylinder. During various phases of filter operation, vacuum forces generated by the vacuum source cooperate with either hydrodynamically or hydrostatically generated forces, which together act upon columns of filtrate in the filtrate conduits as the cylinder rotates.

column13: Systems, including apparatus and methods, for harvesting a product with a mobile harvester so as to minimize the amount of product lost during harvesting. The disclosed systems include an array of catcher plates designed to surround a plant to be harvested, in a manner that minimizes the possibility of harvested product dropping through the plates to the ground and thus being lost. These systems may be useful for harvesting a wide variety of products that grow on plants such as trees or bushes, including without limitation berries, fruit, and coffee beans.

column12: Wax dispersions and their use in the manufacture of sheets or moulded bodies.
column13: An organic polyisocyanate composition contains from 99 to 60 parts by weight of a liquid organic polyisocyanate and from 1 to 40 parts of a 90:10 to 10:90 mixture of a wax and a liquid ester having a molecular weight of at least 250, for example an alkyl ester of an aliphatic carboxylic acid derived from an alkyl alcohol containing from 3 to 30 carbon atoms and a saturated or unsaturated fatty acid containing from 10 to 25 carbon atoms. The composition is useful for the manufacture of sheets or moulded bodies by the hot- pressing of a lignocellulosic material and promotes release of the material from the press. The composition is preferably applied in the form of an aqueous emulsion.

column12: METHOD FOR CALIBRATING A COORDINATE MEASURING MACHINE AND THE LIKE AND SYSTEM THEREFOR
column13: Method (FIGURES 4A through 4C) and system (FIGURE 3) are disclosed for automatically calibrating a coordinate measuring machine (CMM) (10). The system guides an operator through instrument set-up and data collection procedures. The system automatically con­verts the collected data into error compensation or axis correction data which represents 21 different geometry errors (i.e. pitch, yaw, roll etc.) of the CMM (10). The error compensation data is then trans­ferred to a CMM measurement processor (36) for subse­quent use by the CMM (10) during operation thereof to thereby compensate the CMM (10) for its entire measuring volume (102).

column13: <PICT:1108937/C6-C7/1> In a method of electro-chemical machining in which the workpiece forms the anode and the tool the cathode and electrolyte is present between them, relative rotation is effected between the tool and the surface of the workpiece and the working face of the tool comprises at least one electrically conducting area in the form of a sector bounded by radii extending from the axis of rotation, and at least one non-conducting area, whereby the current flowing is concentrated in the conducting surface areas of the tool. The electrolyte may be fed through an axial passage in the tool, to its working face. The conducting sectors may be slightly recessed below the non-conductive areas. The tool may be formed either of non-conductive material with an inset portion of conductive material, Fig. 2a (not shown) or may be formed of conductive material, part of the working pace being covered with non-conductive material e.g. lacquer Fig. 3 (not shown). The embodiment shown comprises a metal base portion 15 formed with a projecting segment 17 which occupies an area cut out of an insulating portion 16. Annular ridges 13, 14 are cut in both insulating material and the conducting area 17, so as to form corresponding annular grooves in the workpiece.

column13: Novel tools and techniques for providing a subscriber with converged voice services, in which calls to one of the subscriber's telephone numbers is routed to some or all of the subscriber's telephone numbers (e.g., sequentially or simultaneously, depending on system configuration and/or subscriber preference). Some implementations employ a VoIP switch to handle call distribution among the subscriber's various phone lines, even if some (or all) of the subscribers telephone lines are not VoIP lines. In such implementations, upon receiving an incoming call directed to one of the subscriber's lines, a service switching point will route the call to a VoIP switch. Instructed by an application server, the VoIP switch will set up call legs (e.g., via the PSTN) to one or more of the subscribers' telephone numbers. Optionally, when one of the call legs is answered, the application server will instruct the VoIP switch to disconnect the other call legs.
